11
111Kg 1:1 Now King David was old and getting on in years. Although they covered him with bedclothes, he could not get warm.
111Kg 1:2 So his servants said to him: "Let us search for a young virgin for my lord the king. She is to attend the king and be his caregiver. She is to lie by your side so that my lord the king will get warm."
111Kg 1:3 They searched for a beautiful girl throughout the territory of Israel; they found Abishag the Shunammite and brought her to the king.
111Kg 1:4 The girl was of unsurpassed beauty, and she became the king's caregiver. She served him, but he was not intimate with her.
111Kg 1:5 Adonijah son of Haggith kept exalting himself, saying, "I will be king!" He also assembled chariots, cavalry, and 50 men to run ahead of him.
111Kg 1:6 But his father had never once reprimanded him by saying, "Why do you act this way?" In addition, he was quite handsome and was born after Absalom.
111Kg 1:7 He conspired with Joab son of Zeruiah and with Abiathar the priest. They supported Adonijah,
111Kg 1:8 but Zadok the priest, Benaiah son of Jehoiada, Nathan the prophet, Shimei, Rei, and David's warriors did not side with Adonijah.
111Kg 1:9 Adonijah sacrificed sheep, oxen, and fattened cattle near the stone of Zoheleth, which is next to En-rogel. He invited all his royal brothers and all the men of Judah, the servants of the king,
111Kg 1:10 but he did not invite Nathan the prophet, Benaiah, the warriors, or his brother Solomon.
111Kg 1:11 Then Nathan said to Bathsheba, Solomon's mother, "Have you not heard that Adonijah son of Haggith has become king and our lord David does not know [it]?
111Kg 1:12 Now please come and let me advise you. Save your life and the life of your son Solomon.
111Kg 1:13 Go, approach King David and say to him, 'My lord king, did you not swear to your servant: Your son Solomon is to become king after me, and he is the one who is to sit on my throne? So why has Adonijah become king?'
111Kg 1:14 At that moment, while you are still there speaking with the king, I'll come in after you and confirm your words."
111Kg 1:15 So Bathsheba went to the king in his bedroom. Since the king was very old, Abishag the Shunammite was serving him.
111Kg 1:16 Bathsheba bowed down and paid homage to the king, and he asked, "What do you want?"
111Kg 1:17 She replied, "My lord, you swore to your servant by the LORD your God, 'Your son Solomon is to become king after me, and he is the one who is to sit on my throne.'
111Kg 1:18 Now look, Adonijah has become king. And, my lord king, you didn't know [it].
111Kg 1:19 He has lavishly sacrificed oxen, fattened cattle, and sheep. He invited all the king's sons, Abiathar the priest, and Joab the commander of the army, but he did not invite your servant Solomon.
111Kg 1:20 Now, my lord king, the eyes of all Israel are on you to tell them who will sit on the throne of my lord the king after him.
111Kg 1:21 Otherwise, when my lord the king rests with his fathers, I and my son Solomon will be regarded as criminals."
111Kg 1:22 At that moment, while she was still speaking with the king, Nathan the prophet arrived,
111Kg 1:23 and it was announced to the king, "Nathan the prophet is here." He came into the king's presence and bowed to him with his face to the ground.
111Kg 1:24 "My lord king," Nathan said, "did you say, 'Adonijah is to become king after me, and he is the one who is to sit on my throne?'
111Kg 1:25 For today he went down and lavishly sacrificed oxen, fattened cattle, and sheep. He invited all the sons of the king, the commanders of the army, and Abiathar the priest. And look! They're eating and drinking in his presence, and they're saying, 'Long live King Adonijah!'
111Kg 1:26 But he did not invite me-- me, your servant-- or Zadok the priest or Benaiah son of Jehoiada or your servant Solomon.
111Kg 1:27 I'm certain my lord the king would not have let this happen without letting your servant know who will sit on my lord the king's throne after him."
111Kg 1:28 King David responded by saying, "Call in Bathsheba for me." So she came into the king's presence and stood before him.
111Kg 1:29 The king swore an oath and said, "As the LORD lives, who has redeemed my life from every difficulty,
111Kg 1:30 just as I swore to you by the LORD God of Israel: Your son Solomon is to become king after me, and he is the one who is to sit on my throne in my place, that is exactly what I will do this very day."
111Kg 1:31 Bathsheba bowed with her face to the ground, paying homage to the king, and said, "May my lord King David live forever!"
111Kg 1:32 King David then said, "Call in Zadok the priest, Nathan the prophet, and Benaiah son of Jehoiada for me." So they came into the king's presence.
111Kg 1:33 The king said to them, "Take my servants with you, have my son Solomon ride on my own mule, and take him down to Gihon.
111Kg 1:34 There, Zadok the priest and Nathan the prophet are to anoint him as king over Israel. You are to blow the ram's horn and say, 'Long live King Solomon!'
111Kg 1:35 You are to come up after him, and he is to come in and sit on my throne. He is the one who is to become king in my place; he is the one I have commanded to be ruler over Israel and Judah."
111Kg 1:36 " Amen," Benaiah son of Jehoiada replied to the king. "May the LORD, the God of my lord the king, so affirm it.
111Kg 1:37 Just as the LORD was with my lord the king, so may He be with Solomon and make his throne greater than the throne of my lord King David."
111Kg 1:38 Then Zadok the priest, Nathan the prophet, Benaiah son of Jehoiada, the Cherethites, and the Pelethites went down, had Solomon ride on King David's mule, and took him to Gihon.
111Kg 1:39 Zadok the priest took the horn of oil from the tabernacle and anointed Solomon. Then they blew the ram's horn, and all the people proclaimed, "Long live King Solomon!"
111Kg 1:40 All the people followed him, playing flutes and rejoicing with such a great joy that the earth split open from the sound.
111Kg 1:41 Adonijah and all the invited guests who were with him heard [the noise] as they finished eating. Joab heard the sound of the ram's horn and said, "Why is the town in such an uproar?"
111Kg 1:42 He was still speaking when Jonathan son of Abiathar the priest, suddenly arrived. Adonijah said, "Come in, for you are an excellent man, and you must be bringing good news."
111Kg 1:43 "Unfortunately not," Jonathan answered him. "Our lord King David has made Solomon king.
111Kg 1:44 And with Solomon, the king has sent Zadok the priest, Nathan the prophet, Benaiah son of Jehoiada, the Cherethites, and the Pelethites, and they have had him ride on the king's mule.
111Kg 1:45 Zadok the priest and Nathan the prophet have anointed him king in Gihon. They have gone from there rejoicing. The town has been in an uproar; that's the noise you heard.
111Kg 1:46 Solomon has even taken his seat on the royal throne.
111Kg 1:47 "The king's servants have also gone to congratulate our lord King David, saying, 'May your God make the name of Solomon more famous than your name, and may He make his throne greater than your throne.' Then the king bowed in worship on his bed.
111Kg 1:48 And the king went on to say this: 'May the LORD God of Israel be praised! Today He has provided one to sit on my throne, and I am a witness.'"
111Kg 1:49 Then all of Adonijah's guests got up trembling and went their separate ways.
111Kg 1:50 Adonijah was afraid of Solomon, so he got up and went to take hold of the horns of the altar.
111Kg 1:51 It was reported to Solomon: "Look, Adonijah fears King Solomon, and he has taken hold of the horns of the altar, saying, 'Let King Solomon first swear to me that he will not kill his servant with the sword.'"
111Kg 1:52 Then Solomon said, "If he is a man of character, then not a single hair of his will fall to the ground, but if evil is found in him, then he dies."
111Kg 1:53 So King Solomon sent for him, and they took him down from the altar. He came and paid homage to King Solomon, and Solomon said to him, "Go to your home."
111Kg 2:1 As the time approached for David to die, he instructed his son Solomon,
111Kg 2:2 "As for me, I am going the way of all of the earth. Be strong and brave,
111Kg 2:3 and keep your obligation to the LORD your God to walk in His ways and to keep His statutes, commandments, judgments, and testimonies. This is written in the law of Moses, so that you will have success in everything you do and wherever you turn,
111Kg 2:4 and so that the LORD will carry out His promise that He made to me: 'If your sons are careful to walk faithfully before Me with their whole mind and heart, you will never fail to have a man on the throne of Israel.'
111Kg 2:5 "You also know what Joab son of Zeruiah did to me and what he did to the two commanders of Israel's army, Abner son of Ner and Amasa son of Jether. He murdered them [in a time] of peace to avenge blood shed in war. He spilled that blood on his own waistband and on the sandals of his feet.
111Kg 2:6 Act according to your wisdom, and do not let his gray head descend to Sheol in peace.
111Kg 2:7 "Show loyalty to the sons of Barzillai the Gileadite and let them be among those who eat at your table because they supported me when I fled from your brother Absalom.
111Kg 2:8 "Keep an eye on Shimei son of Gera, the Benjaminite from Bahurim who is with you. He uttered malicious curses against me the day I went to Mahanaim. But he came down to meet me at the Jordan River, and I swore to him by the LORD: 'I will never kill you with the sword.'
111Kg 2:9 So don't let him go unpunished, for you are a wise man. You know how to deal with him to bring his gray head down to Sheol with blood."
111Kg 2:10 Then David rested with his fathers and was buried in the city of David.
111Kg 2:11 The [length of] time David reigned over Israel was 40 years: he reigned seven years in Hebron and 33 years in Jerusalem.
111Kg 2:12 Solomon sat on the throne of his father David, and his kingship was firmly established.
111Kg 2:13 Now Adonijah son of Haggith came to Bathsheba, Solomon's mother. She asked, "Do you come peacefully?" "Peacefully," he replied,
111Kg 2:14 and then asked, "May I talk with you?" "Go ahead," she answered.
111Kg 2:15 "You know the kingship was mine," he said. "All Israel expected me to be king, but then the kingship was turned over to my brother, for the LORD gave it to him.
111Kg 2:16 So now I have just one request of you; don't turn me down." She said to him, "Go on."
111Kg 2:17 He replied, "Please speak to King Solomon since he won't turn you down. Let him give me Abishag the Shunammite as a wife."
111Kg 2:18 "Very well," Bathsheba replied. "I will speak to the king for you."
111Kg 2:19 So Bathsheba went to King Solomon to speak to him about Adonijah. The king stood up to greet her, bowed to her, sat down on his throne, and had a throne placed for the king's mother. So she sat down at his right hand.
111Kg 2:20 Then she said, "I have just one small request of you. Don't turn me down." "[Go ahead and] ask, mother," the king replied, "for I won't turn you down."
111Kg 2:21 So she said, "Let Abishag the Shunammite be given to your brother Adonijah as a wife."
111Kg 2:22 King Solomon answered his mother, "Why are you requesting Abishag the Shunammite for Adonijah? Since he is my elder brother, you might as well ask the kingship for him, for Abiathar the priest, and for Joab son of Zeruiah."
111Kg 2:23 Then Solomon took an oath by the LORD: "May God punish me and do so severely if Adonijah has not made this request at the cost of his life.
111Kg 2:24 And now, as the LORD lives, the One who established me, seated me on the throne of my father David, and made me a dynasty as He promised-- I swear Adonijah will be put to death today!"
111Kg 2:25 Then King Solomon gave the order to Benaiah son of Jehoiada, who struck down Adonijah, and he died.
111Kg 2:26 The king said to Abiathar the priest, "Go to your fields in Anathoth. Even though you deserve to die, I will not put you to death today, since you carried the ark of the Lord God in the presence of my father David and you suffered through all that my father suffered."
111Kg 2:27 So Solomon banished Abiathar from being the LORD's priest, and it fulfilled the LORD's prophecy He had spoken at Shiloh against Eli's family.
111Kg 2:28 The news reached Joab. Since he had supported Adonijah but not Absalom, Joab fled to the LORD's tabernacle and took hold of the horns of the altar.
111Kg 2:29 It was reported to King Solomon: "Joab has fled to the LORD's tabernacle and is now beside the altar." Then Solomon sent Benaiah son of Jehoiada and told [him], "Go and strike him down!"
111Kg 2:30 So Benaiah went to the tabernacle and said to Joab, "This is what the king says: 'Come out!' " But Joab said, "No, for I will die here." So Benaiah took a message back to the king, "This is what Joab said, and this is how he answered me."
111Kg 2:31 The king said to him, "Do just as he says. Strike him down and bury him in order to remove from me and from my father's house the blood that Joab shed without just cause.
111Kg 2:32 The LORD will bring back his own blood on his own head because he struck down two men more righteous and better than he, without my father David's knowledge. With his sword, Joab murdered Abner son of Ner, commander of Israel's army, and Amasa son of Jether, commander of Judah's army.
111Kg 2:33 Their blood will come back on Joab's head and on the head of his descendants forever, but for David, his descendants, his dynasty, and his throne, there will be peace from the LORD forever."
111Kg 2:34 Benaiah son of Jehoiada went up, struck down Joab, and put him to death. He was buried at his house in the wilderness.
111Kg 2:35 Then the king appointed Benaiah son of Jehoiada in Joab's place over the army, and he appointed Zadok the priest in Abiathar's place.
111Kg 2:36 Then the king summoned Shimei and said to him, "Build a house for yourself in Jerusalem and live there, but don't leave there [and go] anywhere else.
111Kg 2:37 On the day you do leave and cross the Kidron Valley, know for sure that you will certainly die. Your blood will be on your own head."
111Kg 2:38 Shimei said to the king, "The sentence is fair; your servant will do as my lord the king has spoken." And Shimei lived in Jerusalem for a long time.
111Kg 2:39 But then, at the end of three years, two of Shimei's slaves ran away to Achish son of Maacah, king of Gath. Shimei was informed, "Look, your slaves are in Gath."
111Kg 2:40 So Shimei saddled his donkey and set out to Achish at Gath to search for his slaves. He went and brought them back from Gath.
111Kg 2:41 It was reported to Solomon that Shimei had gone from Jerusalem to Gath and had returned.
111Kg 2:42 So the king summoned Shimei and said to him, "Didn't I make you swear by the LORD and warn you, saying, 'On the day you leave and go anywhere else, know for sure that you will certainly die'? And you said to me, 'The sentence is fair; I will obey.'
111Kg 2:43 So why have you not kept the LORD's oath and the command that I gave you?"
111Kg 2:44 The king also said, "You yourself know all the evil that you did to my father David. Therefore, the LORD has brought back your evil on your head,
111Kg 2:45 but King Solomon will be blessed, and David's throne will remain established before the LORD forever."
111Kg 2:46 Then the king commanded Benaiah son of Jehoiada, and he went out and struck Shimei down, and he died. So the kingdom was established in Solomon's hand.
111Kg 3:1 Solomon made an alliance with Pharaoh king of Egypt by marrying Pharaoh's daughter. Solomon brought her to the city of David until he finished building his palace, the LORD's temple, and the wall surrounding Jerusalem.
111Kg 3:2 However, the people were sacrificing on the high places, because until that time a temple for the LORD's name had not been built.
111Kg 3:3 Solomon loved the LORD by walking in the statutes of his father David, but he also sacrificed and burned incense on the high places.
111Kg 3:4 The king went to Gibeon to sacrifice there because it was the most famous high place. He offered 1,000 burnt offerings on that altar.
111Kg 3:5 At Gibeon the LORD appeared to Solomon in a dream at night. God said, "Ask. What should I give you?"
111Kg 3:6 And Solomon replied, "You have shown great and faithful love to Your servant, my father David, because he walked before You in faithfulness, righteousness, and integrity. You have continued this great and faithful love for him by giving him a son to sit on his throne, as it is today.
111Kg 3:7 "LORD my God, You have now made Your servant king in my father David's place. Yet I am just a youth with no experience in leadership.
111Kg 3:8 Your servant is among Your people You have chosen, a people too numerous to be numbered or counted.
111Kg 3:9 So give Your servant an obedient heart to judge Your people and to discern between good and evil. For who is able to judge this great people of Yours?"
111Kg 3:10 Now it pleased the Lord that Solomon had requested this.
111Kg 3:11 So God said to him, "Because you have requested this and did not ask for long life or riches for yourself, or the death of your enemies, but you asked discernment for yourself to understand justice,
111Kg 3:12 I will therefore do what you have asked. I will give you a wise and understanding heart, so that there has never been anyone like you before and never will be again.
111Kg 3:13 In addition, I will give you what you did not ask for: both riches and honor, so that no man in any kingdom will be your equal during your entire life.
111Kg 3:14 If you walk in My ways and keep My statutes and commandments just as your father David did, I will give you a long life."
111Kg 3:15 Then Solomon woke up and realized it had been a dream. He went to Jerusalem, stood before the ark of the Lord's covenant, and offered burnt offerings and fellowship offerings. Then he held a feast for all his servants.
111Kg 3:16 Then two women who were prostitutes came to the king and stood before him.
111Kg 3:17 One woman said, "Please my lord, this woman and I live in the same house, and I had a baby while she was in the house.
111Kg 3:18 On the third day after I gave birth, she also had a baby and we were alone. No one else was with us in the house; just the two of us were there.
111Kg 3:19 During the night this woman's son died because she lay on him.
111Kg 3:20 She got up in the middle of the night and took my son from my side while your servant was asleep. She laid him at her breast, and she put her dead son in my arms.
111Kg 3:21 When I got up in the morning to nurse my son, I discovered he was dead. That morning, when I looked closely at him I realized that he was not the son I gave birth to."
111Kg 3:22 "No," the other woman said. "My son is the living one; your son is the dead one." The first woman said, "No, your son is the dead one; my son is the living one." So they argued before the king.
111Kg 3:23 The king replied, "This woman says, 'This is my son who is alive, and your son is dead,' but that woman says, 'No, your son is dead, and my son is alive.'"
111Kg 3:24 The king continued, "Bring me a sword." So they brought the sword to the king.
111Kg 3:25 Solomon said, "Cut the living boy in two and give half to one and half to the other."
111Kg 3:26 The woman whose son was alive spoke to the king because she felt great compassion for her son. "My lord, give her the living baby," she said, "but please don't have him killed!" But the other one said, "He will not be mine or yours. Cut [him in two]!"
111Kg 3:27 The king responded, "Give the living baby to the first woman, and don't kill him. She is his mother."
111Kg 3:28 All Israel heard about the judgment the king had given, and they stood in awe of the king because they saw that God's wisdom was in him to carry out justice.
111Kg 4:1 King Solomon ruled over Israel,
111Kg 4:2 and these were his officials: Azariah son of Zadok, priest;
111Kg 4:3 Elihoreph and Ahijah the sons of Shisha, secretaries; Jehoshaphat son of Ahilud, historian;
111Kg 4:4 Benaiah son of Jehoiada, in charge of the army; Zadok and Abiathar, priests;
111Kg 4:5 Azariah son of Nathan, in charge of the deputies; Zabud son of Nathan, a priest and adviser to the king;
111Kg 4:6 Ahishar, in charge of the palace; and Adoniram son of Abda, in charge of forced labor.
111Kg 4:7 Solomon had 12 deputies for all Israel. They provided food for the king and his household; each one made provision for one month out of the year.
111Kg 4:8 These were their names: Ben-hur, in the hill country of Ephraim;
111Kg 4:9 Ben-deker, in Makaz, Shaalbim, Beth-shemesh, and Elon-beth-hanan;
111Kg 4:10 Ben-hesed, in Arubboth (he had Socoh and the whole land of Hepher);
111Kg 4:11 Ben-abinadab, in all Naphath-dor (Taphath daughter of Solomon was his wife);
111Kg 4:12 Baana son of Ahilud, in Taanach, Megiddo, and all Beth-shean which is beside Zarethan below Jezreel, from Beth-shean to Abel-meholah, as far as the other side of Jokmeam;
111Kg 4:13 Ben-geber, in Ramoth-gilead (he had the villages of Jair son of Manasseh, which are in Gilead, and he had the region of Argob, which is in Bashan, 60 great cities with walls and bronze bars);
111Kg 4:14 Ahinadab son of Iddo, [in] Mahanaim;
111Kg 4:15 Ahimaaz, in Naphtali (he also had married a daughter of Solomon-- Basemath);
111Kg 4:16 Baana son of Hushai, in Asher and Bealoth;
111Kg 4:17 Jehoshaphat son of Paruah, in Issachar;
111Kg 4:18 Shimei son of Ela, in Benjamin;
111Kg 4:19 Geber son of Uri, in the land of Gilead, the country of Sihon king of the Amorites and of Og king of Bashan. There was one deputy in the land of Judah.
111Kg 4:20 Judah and Israel were as numerous as the sand by the sea; [they were] eating, drinking, and rejoicing.
111Kg 4:21  Solomon ruled over all the kingdoms from the Euphrates River to the land of the Philistines and as far as the border of Egypt. They offered tribute and served Solomon all the days of his life.
111Kg 4:22 Solomon's provisions for one day were 150 bushels of fine flour and 300 bushels of meal,
111Kg 4:23 10 fattened oxen, 20 range oxen, and 100 sheep, besides deer, gazelles, roebucks, and pen-fed poultry,
111Kg 4:24 for he had dominion over everything west of the Euphrates from Tiphsah to Gaza and over all the kings west of the Euphrates. He had peace on all his surrounding borders.
111Kg 4:25 Throughout Solomon's [reign], Judah and Israel lived in safety from Dan to Beer-sheba, each man under his own vine and his own fig tree.
111Kg 4:26 Solomon had 40,000 stalls of horses for his chariots, and 12,000 horsemen.
111Kg 4:27 Each of those deputies for a month in turn provided food for King Solomon and for everyone who came to King Solomon's table. They neglected nothing.
111Kg 4:28 Each man brought the barley and the straw for the chariot teams and the other horses to the required place according to his assignment.
111Kg 4:29 God gave Solomon wisdom, very great insight, and understanding as [vast] as the sand on the seashore.
111Kg 4:30 Solomon's wisdom was greater than the wisdom of all the people of the East, greater than all the wisdom of Egypt.
111Kg 4:31 He was wiser than anyone-- wiser than Ethan the Ezrahite, and Heman, Calcol, and Darda, sons of Mahol. His reputation extended to all the surrounding nations.
111Kg 4:32 Solomon composed 3,000 proverbs, and his songs numbered 1,005.
111Kg 4:33 He described trees, from the cedar in Lebanon to the hyssop growing out of the wall. He also taught about animals, birds, reptiles, and fish.
111Kg 4:34 People came from everywhere, [sent] by every king on earth who had heard of his wisdom, to listen to Solomon's wisdom.
111Kg 5:1 Hiram king of Tyre sent his servants to Solomon when he heard that he had been anointed king in his father's place, for Hiram had always been friends with David.
111Kg 5:2 Solomon sent [this message] to Hiram:
111Kg 5:3 "You know my father David was not able to build a temple for the name of the LORD his God. This was because of the warfare all around him until the LORD put his enemies under his feet.
111Kg 5:4 The LORD my God has now given me rest all around; there is no enemy or crisis.
111Kg 5:5 So I plan to build a temple for the name of the LORD my God, according to what the LORD promised my father David: 'I will put your son on your throne in your place, and he will build the temple for My name.'
111Kg 5:6 "Therefore, command that cedars from Lebanon be cut down for me. My servants will be with your servants, and I will pay your servants' wages according to whatever you say, for you know that not a man among us knows how to cut timber like the Sidonians."
111Kg 5:7 When Hiram heard Solomon's words, he greatly rejoiced and said, "May the LORD be praised today! He has given David a wise son to be over this great people!"
111Kg 5:8 Then Hiram sent [a reply] to Solomon, saying, "I have heard your message; I will do everything you want regarding the cedar and cypress timber.
111Kg 5:9 My servants will bring [the logs] down from Lebanon to the sea, and I will make them into rafts to go by sea to the place you indicate. I will break them apart there, and you can take them away. You then can meet my needs by providing my household with food."
111Kg 5:10 So Hiram provided Solomon with all the cedar and cypress timber he wanted,
111Kg 5:11 and Solomon provided Hiram with 100,000 bushels of wheat as food for his household and 110,000 gallons of beaten oil. Solomon did this for Hiram year after year.
111Kg 5:12 The LORD gave Solomon wisdom, as He had promised him. There was peace between Hiram and Solomon, and the two of them made a treaty.
111Kg 5:13 Then King Solomon drafted forced laborers from all Israel; the labor force numbered 30,000 men.
111Kg 5:14 He sent 10,000 to Lebanon each month in shifts; one month they were in Lebanon, two months they were at home. Adoniram was in charge of the forced labor.
111Kg 5:15 Solomon had 70,000 porters and 80,000 stonecutters in the mountains,
111Kg 5:16 not including his 3,300 deputies in charge of the work. They ruled over the people doing the work.
111Kg 5:17 The king commanded them to quarry large, costly stones to lay the foundation of the temple with dressed stones.
111Kg 5:18 So Solomon's builders and Hiram's builders, along with the Gebalites, quarried [the stone] and prepared the timber and stone for the temple's construction.
111Kg 6:1 Solomon [began to] build the temple for the LORD in the four hundred eightieth year after the Israelites came out from the land of Egypt, in the fourth year of his reign over Israel, in the second month, in the month of Ziv.
111Kg 6:2 The temple that King Solomon built for the LORD was 90 feet long, 30 feet wide, and 45 feet high.
111Kg 6:3 The portico in front of the temple sanctuary was 30 feet long extending across the temple's width, and 15 feet deep in front of the temple.
111Kg 6:4 He also made windows with beveled frames for the temple.
111Kg 6:5 He then built a chambered structure along the temple wall, encircling the walls of the temple, that is, the sanctuary and the inner sanctuary. And he made side chambers all around.
111Kg 6:6 The lowest chamber was seven and a half feet wide, the middle was nine feet wide, and the third was 10 and a half feet wide. He also provided offset ledges for the temple all around the outside so that nothing would be inserted into the temple walls.
111Kg 6:7 The temple's construction used finished stones cut at the quarry so that no hammer, chisel, or any iron tool was heard in the temple while it was being built.
111Kg 6:8 The door for the lowest side chamber was on the right side of the temple. They went up a stairway to the middle [chamber], and from the middle to the third.
111Kg 6:9 When he finished building the temple, he paneled it with boards and planks of cedar.
111Kg 6:10 He built the chambers along the entire temple, joined to the temple with cedar beams; [each story was] seven and a half feet high.
111Kg 6:11 The word of the LORD came to Solomon:
111Kg 6:12 "As for this temple you are building-- if you walk in My statutes, execute My ordinances, and keep all My commandments by walking in them, I will fulfill My promise to you, which I made to your father David.
111Kg 6:13 I will live among the Israelites and not abandon My people Israel."
111Kg 6:14 When Solomon finished building the temple,
111Kg 6:15 he paneled the interior temple walls with cedar boards; from the temple floor to the surface of the ceiling he overlaid the interior with wood. He also overlaid the floor with cypress boards.
111Kg 6:16 Then he lined 30 feet of the rear of the temple with cedar boards from the floor to the surface of the ceiling, and he built the interior as an inner sanctuary, the most holy place.
111Kg 6:17 The temple, that is, the sanctuary in front of the most holy place, was 60 feet long.
111Kg 6:18 The cedar paneling inside the temple was carved with [ornamental] gourds and flower blossoms. Everything was cedar; not a stone could be seen.
111Kg 6:19 He prepared the inner sanctuary inside the temple to put the ark of the LORD's covenant there.
111Kg 6:20 The interior of the sanctuary was 30 feet long, 30 feet wide, and 30 feet high; he overlaid it with pure gold. He also overlaid the cedar altar.
111Kg 6:21 Next, Solomon overlaid the interior of the temple with pure gold, and he hung gold chains across the front of the inner sanctuary and overlaid it with gold.
111Kg 6:22 So he added the gold overlay to the entire temple until everything was completely finished, including the entire altar that belongs in the inner sanctuary.
111Kg 6:23 In the inner sanctuary he made two cherubim 15 feet high out of olive wood.
111Kg 6:24 One wing of the [first] cherub was seven and a half feet long, and the other wing was seven and a half feet long. The wingspan was 15 feet from tip to tip.
111Kg 6:25 The second cherub also was 15 feet; both cherubim had the same size and shape.
111Kg 6:26 The first cherub's height was 15 feet and so was the second cherub's.
111Kg 6:27 Then he put the cherubim inside the inner temple. Since their wings were spread out, the first one's wing touched [one] wall while the second cherub's wing touched the other wall, and in the middle of the temple their wings were touching wing to wing.
111Kg 6:28 He also overlaid the cherubim with gold.
111Kg 6:29 He carved all the surrounding temple walls with carved engravings-- cherubim, palm trees and flower blossoms-- in both the inner and outer sanctuaries.
111Kg 6:30 He overlaid the temple floor with gold in both the inner and outer sanctuaries.
111Kg 6:31 For the entrance of the inner sanctuary, he made olive wood doors. The pillars of the doorposts were five-sided.
111Kg 6:32 The two doors were made of olive wood. He carved cherubim, palm trees and flower blossoms on them and overlaid them with gold, hammering gold over the cherubim and palm trees.
111Kg 6:33 In the same way, he made four-sided olive wood doorposts for the sanctuary entrance.
111Kg 6:34 The two doors were made of cypress wood; the first door had two folding sides, and the second door had two folding panels.
111Kg 6:35 He carved cherubim, palm trees and flower blossoms on them and overlaid them with gold applied evenly over the carving.
111Kg 6:36 He built the inner courtyard with three rows of dressed stone and a row of trimmed cedar beams.
111Kg 6:37 The foundation of the LORD's temple was laid in [Solomon's] fourth year in the month of Ziv.
111Kg 6:38 In [his] eleventh year in the eighth month, in the month of Bul, the temple was completed in every detail and according to every specification. So he built it in seven years.
111Kg 7:1 Solomon completed his entire palace-complex after 13 years of construction.
111Kg 7:2 He built the House of the Forest of Lebanon. It was 150 feet long, 75 feet wide, and 45 feet high on four rows of cedar pillars, with cedar beams on top of the pillars.
111Kg 7:3 It was paneled above with cedar at the top of the chambers that [rested] on 45 pillars, fifteen per row.
111Kg 7:4 There were three rows of window frames, facing each other in three tiers.
111Kg 7:5 All the doors and doorposts had rectangular frames, the openings facing each other in three tiers.
111Kg 7:6 He made the hall of pillars 75 feet long and 45 feet wide. A portico was in front of the pillars, and a canopy with pillars were in front of them.
111Kg 7:7 He made the Hall of the Throne where he would judge-- the Hall of Judgment. It was paneled with cedar from the floor to the rafters.
111Kg 7:8 Solomon's own palace where he would live, in the other courtyard behind the hall, was of similar construction. And he made a house like this hall for Pharaoh's daughter, his wife.
111Kg 7:9 All of these [buildings] were of costly stones, cut to size and sawed with saws on the inner and outer surfaces, from foundation to coping and from the outside to the great courtyard.
111Kg 7:10 The foundation was made of large, costly stones 12 and 15 feet long.
111Kg 7:11 Above were also costly stones, cut to size, as well as cedar wood.
111Kg 7:12 Around the great courtyard, as well as the inner courtyard of the LORD's temple and the portico of the temple, were three rows of dressed stone and a row of trimmed cedar beams.
111Kg 7:13 King Solomon had Hiram brought from Tyre.
111Kg 7:14 He was a widow's son from the tribe of Naphtali, and his father was a man of Tyre, a bronze craftsman. Hiram had great skill, understanding, and knowledge to do every kind of bronze work. So he came to King Solomon and carried out all his work.
111Kg 7:15 He cast two [hollow] bronze pillars: each 27 feet high and 18 feet in circumference.
111Kg 7:16 He also made two capitals of cast bronze to set on top of the pillars; seven and a half feet was the height of the first capital, and seven and a half feet was also the height of the second capital.
111Kg 7:17 The capitals on top of the pillars had gratings of latticework, wreaths made of chainwork-- seven for the first capital and seven for the second.
111Kg 7:18 He made the pillars with two encircling rows of pomegranates on the one grating to cover the capital on top; he did the same for the second capital.
111Kg 7:19 And the capitals on top of the pillars in the portico were shaped like lilies, six feet [high].
111Kg 7:20 The capitals on the two pillars were also immediately above the rounded surface next to the grating, and 200 pomegranates were in rows encircling each capital.
111Kg 7:21 He set up the pillars at the portico of the sanctuary: he set up the right pillar and named it Jachin; then he set up the left pillar and named it Boaz.
111Kg 7:22 The tops of the pillars were shaped like lilies. Then the work of the pillars was completed.
111Kg 7:23 He made the cast [metal] reservoir, 15 feet from brim to brim, perfectly round. It was seven and a half feet high and 45 feet in circumference.
111Kg 7:24 [Ornamental] gourds encircled it below the brim, 10 every half yard, completely encircling the reservoir. The gourds were cast in two rows when the reservoir was cast.
111Kg 7:25 It stood on 12 oxen, three facing north, three facing west, three facing south, and three facing east. The reservoir was on top of them and all their hindquarters were toward the center.
111Kg 7:26 The reservoir was three inches thick, and its rim was fashioned like the brim of a cup or of a lily blossom. It held 11,000 gallons.
111Kg 7:27 Then he made 10 bronze water carts. Each water cart was six feet long, six feet wide, and four and a half feet high.
111Kg 7:28 This was the design of the carts: They had frames; the frames were between the cross-pieces,
111Kg 7:29 and on the frames between the cross-pieces were lions, oxen, and cherubim. On the cross-pieces there was a pedestal above, and below the lions and oxen were wreaths of hanging work.
111Kg 7:30 Each cart had four bronze wheels with bronze axles. Underneath the four corners of the basin were cast supports, each next to a wreath.
111Kg 7:31 And the water cart's opening inside the crown on top was 18 inches wide. The opening was round, made as a pedestal 27 inches wide. On it were carvings, but their frames were square, not round.
111Kg 7:32 There were four wheels under the frames, and the wheel axles were part of the water cart; each wheel was 27 inches tall.
111Kg 7:33 The wheels' design was similar to that of chariot wheels: their axles, rims, spokes, and hubs were all of cast metal.
111Kg 7:34 Four supports were at the four corners of each water cart; each support was one piece with the water cart.
111Kg 7:35 At the top of the cart was a band nine inches high encircling it; also, at the top of the cart, its braces and its frames were one piece with it.
111Kg 7:36 He engraved cherubim, lions, and palm trees on the plates of its braces and on its frames, wherever each had space, with encircling wreaths.
111Kg 7:37 In this way he made the 10 water carts using the same casting, dimensions, and shape for all of them.
111Kg 7:38 Then he made 10 bronze basins-- each basin holding 220 gallons and each was six feet wide-- one basin for each of the 10 water carts.
111Kg 7:39 He set five water carts on the right side of the temple and five on the left side. He put the reservoir near the right side of the temple toward the southeast.
111Kg 7:40 Then Hiram made the basins, the shovels, and the sprinkling basins. So Hiram finished all the work that he was doing for King Solomon on the LORD's temple:
111Kg 7:41 two pillars; bowls for the capitals that were on top of the two pillars; the two gratings for covering both bowls of the capitals that were on top of the pillars;
111Kg 7:42 the 400 pomegranates for the two gratings (two rows of pomegranates for each grating covering both capitals' bowls on top of the pillars);
111Kg 7:43 the 10 water carts; the 10 basins on the water carts;
111Kg 7:44 the reservoir; the 12 oxen underneath the reservoir;
111Kg 7:45 and the pots, shovels, and sprinkling basins. All the utensils that Hiram made for King Solomon at the LORD's temple [were made] of burnished bronze.
111Kg 7:46 The king had them cast in clay molds in the Jordan Valley between Succoth and Zarethan.
111Kg 7:47 Solomon left all the utensils unweighed because there were so many; the weight of the bronze was not determined.
111Kg 7:48 Solomon also made all the equipment in the LORD's temple: the gold altar; the gold table that the bread of the Presence was placed on;
111Kg 7:49 the pure gold lampstands in front of the inner sanctuary, five on the right and five on the left; the gold flowers, lamps, and tongs;
111Kg 7:50 the pure gold ceremonial bowls, wick trimmers, sprinkling basins, ladles, and firepans; and the gold hinges for the doors of the inner temple (that is, the most holy place) and for the doors of the temple sanctuary.
111Kg 7:51 So all the work King Solomon did in the LORD's temple was completed. Then Solomon brought in the consecrated things of his father David-- the silver, the gold, and the utensils-- and put them in the treasuries of the LORD's temple.
111Kg 8:1 At that time Solomon assembled the elders of Israel, all the tribal heads and the ancestral leaders of the Israelites before him at Jerusalem in order to bring the ark of the LORD's covenant from Zion, the city of David.
111Kg 8:2 So all the men of Israel were assembled in the presence of King Solomon in the seventh month, the month of Ethanim at the festival.
111Kg 8:3 All the elders of Israel came, and the priests picked up the ark.
111Kg 8:4 The priests and the Levites brought the ark of the LORD, the tent of meeting, and the holy utensils that were in the tent.
111Kg 8:5 King Solomon and the entire congregation of Israel, who had gathered around him and were with him in front of the ark, were sacrificing sheep and cattle that could not be counted or numbered, because there were so many.
111Kg 8:6 The priests brought the ark of the LORD's covenant to its place, into the inner sanctuary of the temple, to the most holy place beneath the wings of the cherubim.
111Kg 8:7 For the cherubim were spreading their wings over the place of the ark, so that the cherubim covered the ark and its poles from above.
111Kg 8:8 The poles were so long that their ends were seen from the holy place in front of the inner sanctuary, but they were not seen from outside [the sanctuary]; they are there to this day.
111Kg 8:9 Nothing was in the ark except the two stone tablets that Moses had put there at Horeb,where the LORD made a covenant with the Israelites when they came out of the land of Egypt.
111Kg 8:10 When the priests came out of the holy place, the cloud filled the LORD's temple,
111Kg 8:11 and because of the cloud, the priests were not able to continue ministering, for the glory of the LORD filled the temple.
111Kg 8:12 Then Solomon said: The LORD said that He would dwell in thick darkness,
111Kg 8:13 but I have indeed built an exalted temple for You, a place for Your dwelling forever.
111Kg 8:14 The king turned around and blessed the entire congregation of Israel while they were standing.
111Kg 8:15 He said: May the LORD God of Israel be praised! He spoke directly to my father David, and He has fulfilled [the promise] by His power. He said,
111Kg 8:16 "Since the day I brought My people Israel out of Egypt, I have not chosen a city to build a temple in among any of the tribes of Israel, so that My name would be there. But I have chosen David to rule My people Israel."
111Kg 8:17 It was in the desire of my father David to build a temple for the name of the LORD God of Israel.
111Kg 8:18 But the LORD said to my father David, "Since it was your desire to build a temple for My name, you have done well to have this desire.
111Kg 8:19 Yet you are not the one to build it; instead, your son, your own offspring, will build it for My name."
111Kg 8:20 The LORD has fulfilled what He promised. I have taken the place of my father David, and I sit on the throne of Israel, as the LORD promised. I have built the temple for the name of the LORD God of Israel.
111Kg 8:21 I have provided a place there for the ark, where the LORD's covenant is that He made with our ancestors when He brought them out of the land of Egypt.
111Kg 8:22 Then Solomon stood before the altar of the LORD in front of the entire congregation of Israel and spread out his hands toward heaven.
111Kg 8:23 He said: LORD God of Israel, there is no God like You in heaven above or on earth below, keeping the gracious covenant with Your servants who walk before You with their whole heart.
111Kg 8:24 You have kept what You promised to Your servant, my father David. You spoke directly [to him] and You fulfilled [Your promise] by Your power as it is today.
111Kg 8:25 Therefore, LORD God of Israel, keep what You promised to Your servant, my father David: You will never fail to have a man to sit before Me on the throne of Israel, if only your sons guard their walk before Me as you have walked before Me.
111Kg 8:26 Now LORD God of Israel, please confirm what You promised to Your servant, my father David.
111Kg 8:27 But will God indeed live on earth? Even heaven, the highest heaven, cannot contain You, much less this temple I have built.
111Kg 8:28 Listen to Your servant's prayer and his petition, LORD my God, so that You may hear the cry and the prayer that Your servant prays before You today,
111Kg 8:29 so that Your eyes may watch over this temple night and day, toward the place where You said: My name will be there, and so that You may hear the prayer that Your servant prays toward this place.
111Kg 8:30 Hear the petition of Your servant and Your people Israel, which they pray toward this place. May You hear in Your dwelling place in heaven. May You hear and forgive.
111Kg 8:31 When a man sins against his neighbor and is forced to take an oath, and he comes to take an oath before Your altar in this temple,
111Kg 8:32 may You hear in heaven and act. May You judge Your servants, condemning the wicked by bringing what he has done on his own head and providing justice for the righteous by rewarding him according to his righteousness.
111Kg 8:33 When Your people Israel are defeated before an enemy, because they have sinned against You, and they return to You and praise Your name, and they pray and plead with You for mercy in this temple,
111Kg 8:34 may You hear in heaven and forgive the sin of Your people Israel. May You restore them to the land You gave their ancestors.
111Kg 8:35 When the skies are shut and there is no rain, because they have sinned against You, and they pray toward this place and praise Your name, and they turn from their sins because You are afflicting them,
111Kg 8:36 may You hear in heaven and forgive the sin of Your servants and Your people Israel, so that You may teach them the good way they should walk in. May You send rain on Your land that You gave Your people for an inheritance.
111Kg 8:37 When there is famine on the earth, when there is pestilence, when there is blight, mildew, locust, or grasshopper, when their enemy besieges them in the region of their fortified cities, [when there is] any plague or illness,
111Kg 8:38 whatever prayer or petition anyone from Your people Israel might have-- each man knowing his own afflictions and spreading out his hands toward this temple--
111Kg 8:39 may You hear in heaven, Your dwelling place, and may You forgive, act, and repay the man, according to all his ways, since You know his heart, for You alone know every human heart,
111Kg 8:40 so that they may fear You all the days they live on the land You gave our ancestors.
111Kg 8:41 Even for the foreigner who is not of Your people Israel but has come from a distant land because of Your name--
111Kg 8:42 for they will hear of Your great name, mighty hand, and outstretched arm, and will come and pray toward this temple--
111Kg 8:43 may You hear in heaven, Your dwelling place, and do according to all the foreigner asks You for. Then all the people on earth will know Your name, to fear You as Your people Israel do and know that this temple I have built is called by Your name.
111Kg 8:44 When Your people go out to fight against their enemies, wherever You send them, and they pray to the LORD in the direction of the city You have chosen and the temple I have built for Your name,
111Kg 8:45 may You hear their prayer and petition in heaven and uphold their cause.
111Kg 8:46 When they sin against You-- for there is no one who does not sin-- and You are angry with them and hand them over to the enemy, and their captors deport them to the enemy's country-- whether distant or nearby--
111Kg 8:47 and when they come to their senses in the land where they were deported and repent and petition You in their captors' land: "We have sinned and done wrong; we have been wicked,"
111Kg 8:48 and when they return to You with their whole mind and heart in the land of their enemies who took them captive, and when they pray to You in the direction of their land that You gave their ancestors, the city You have chosen, and the temple I have built for Your name,
111Kg 8:49 may You hear in heaven, Your dwelling place, their prayer and petition and uphold their cause.
111Kg 8:50 May You forgive Your people who sinned against You and all their rebellions against You, and may You give them compassion in the eyes of their captors, so that they may be compassionate to them.
111Kg 8:51 For they are Your people and Your inheritance; You brought them out of Egypt, out of the middle of an iron furnace.
111Kg 8:52 May Your eyes be open to Your servant's petition and to the petition of Your people Israel, listening to them whenever they call to You.
111Kg 8:53 For You, Lord God, have set them apart as Your inheritance from all the people on earth, as You spoke through Your servant Moses when You brought their ancestors out of Egypt.
111Kg 8:54 When Solomon finished praying this entire prayer and petition to the LORD, he got up from kneeling before the altar of the LORD, with his hands spread out toward heaven,
111Kg 8:55 and he stood and blessed the whole congregation of Israel with a loud voice:
111Kg 8:56 "May the LORD be praised! He has given rest to His people Israel according to all He has said. Not one of all the good promises He made through His servant Moses has failed.
111Kg 8:57 May the LORD our God be with us as He was with our ancestors. May He not abandon us or leave us.
111Kg 8:58 May He incline our hearts toward Him to walk in all His ways and to keep His commands, ordinances, and judgments, which He commanded our ancestors.
111Kg 8:59 May my words I have made my petition with before the LORD be near the LORD our God day and night, so that He may uphold His servant's cause and the cause of His people Israel, as each day requires,
111Kg 8:60 and so that all the peoples of the earth may know that the LORD is God. There is no other!
111Kg 8:61 Let your heart be completely devoted to the LORD our God to walk in His ordinances and to keep His commands, as it is today."
111Kg 8:62 The king and all Israel with him were offering sacrifices in the LORD's presence.
111Kg 8:63 Solomon offered a sacrifice of fellowship offerings to the LORD: 22,000 cattle and 120,000 sheep. In this manner the king and all the Israelites dedicated the LORD's temple.
111Kg 8:64 On the same day, the king consecrated the middle of the courtyard that was in front of the LORD's temple because that was where he offered the burnt offering, the grain offering, and the fat of the fellowship offerings since the bronze altar before the LORD was too small to accommodate the burnt offerings, the grain offerings, and the fat of the fellowship offerings.
111Kg 8:65 Solomon and all Israel with him-- a great assembly, from the entrance of Hamath to the Brook of Egypt-- observed the festival at that time in the presence of the LORD our God, seven days, and seven [more] days-- 14 days.
111Kg 8:66 On the fifteenth day he sent the people away. So they blessed the king and went home to their tents rejoicing and with joyful hearts for all the goodness that the LORD had done for His servant David and for His people Israel.
111Kg 9:1 When Solomon finished building the temple of the LORD, the royal palace, and all that Solomon desired to do,
111Kg 9:2 the LORD appeared to Solomon a second time just as He had appeared to him at Gibeon.
111Kg 9:3 The LORD said to him: I have heard your prayer and petition you have made before Me. I have consecrated this temple you have built, to put My name there forever; My eyes and My heart will be there at all times.
111Kg 9:4 As for you, if you walk before Me as your father David walked, with integrity of heart and uprightness, doing everything I have commanded you, and if you keep My statutes and ordinances,
111Kg 9:5 I will establish your royal throne over Israel forever, as I promised your father David: You will never fail to have a man on the throne of Israel.
111Kg 9:6 If you or your sons turn away from following Me and do not keep My commands-- My statutes that I have set before you-- and if you go and serve other gods and worship them,
111Kg 9:7 I will cut off Israel from the land I gave them, and I will reject the temple I have sanctified for My name. Israel will become an object of scorn and ridicule among all the peoples.
111Kg 9:8 Though this temple is [now] exalted, every passerby will be appalled and will hiss. They will say: Why did the LORD do this to this land and this temple?
111Kg 9:9 Then they will say: Because they abandoned the LORD their God who brought their ancestors out of the land of Egypt. They clung to other gods and worshiped and served them. Because of this, the LORD brought all this ruin on them.
111Kg 9:10 At the end of 20 years during which Solomon had built the two houses, the LORD's temple and the royal palace--
111Kg 9:11 Hiram king of Tyre having supplied him with cedar and cypress logs and gold for his every wish-- King Solomon gave Hiram 20 towns in the land of Galilee.
111Kg 9:12 So Hiram went out from Tyre to look over the towns that Solomon had given him, but he was not pleased with them.
111Kg 9:13 So he said, "What are these towns you've given me, my brother?" So he called them the Land of Cabul, as they are [still called] today.
111Kg 9:14 Now Hiram had sent the king 9,000 pounds of gold.
111Kg 9:15 This is the account of the forced labor that King Solomon had imposed to build the LORD's temple, his own palace, the supporting terraces, the wall of Jerusalem, and Hazor, Megiddo, and Gezer.
111Kg 9:16 Pharaoh king of Egypt had attacked and captured Gezer. He then burned it down, killed the Canaanites who lived in the city, and gave it as a dowry to his daughter, Solomon's wife.
111Kg 9:17 Then Solomon rebuilt Gezer, Lower Beth-horon,
111Kg 9:18 Baalath, Tamar in the Wilderness of Judah,
111Kg 9:19 all the storage cities that belonged to Solomon, the chariot cities, the cavalry cities, and whatever Solomon desired to build in Jerusalem, Lebanon, or anywhere else in the land of his dominion.
111Kg 9:20 As for all the peoples who remained of the Amorites, Hittites, Perizzites, Hivites, and Jebusites, who were not Israelites--
111Kg 9:21 their descendants who remained in the land after them, those whom the Israelites were unable to annihilate-- Solomon imposed forced labor on them; [it is this way] until today.
111Kg 9:22 But Solomon did not consign the Israelites to slavery; they were soldiers, his servants, his commanders, his captains, and commanders of his chariots and his cavalry.
111Kg 9:23 These were the deputies who were over Solomon's work: 550 who ruled over the people doing the work.
111Kg 9:24 Pharaoh's daughter moved from the city of David to the house that Solomon had built for her; he then built the terraces.
111Kg 9:25 Three times a year Solomon offered burnt offerings and fellowship offerings on the altar he had built for the LORD, and he burned incense with them in the LORD's presence. So he completed the temple.
111Kg 9:26 King Solomon put together a fleet of ships at Ezion-geber, which is near Eloth on the shore of the Red Sea in the land of Edom.
111Kg 9:27 With the fleet, Hiram sent his servants, experienced seamen, along with Solomon's servants.
111Kg 9:28 They went to Ophir and acquired gold there-- 16 tons-- and delivered it to Solomon.
111Kg 10:1 The queen of Sheba heard about Solomon's fame connected with the name of the LORD and came to test him with difficult questions.
111Kg 10:2 She came to Jerusalem with a very large retinue, with camels bearing spices, gold in great abundance, and precious stones. She came to Solomon and spoke to him about everything that was on her mind.
111Kg 10:3 So Solomon answered all her questions; nothing was too difficult for the king to explain to her.
111Kg 10:4 When the queen of Sheba observed all of Solomon's wisdom, the palace he had built,
111Kg 10:5 the food at his table, his servants' residence, his attendants' service and their attire, his cupbearers, and the burnt offerings he offered at the LORD's temple, it took her breath away.
111Kg 10:6 She said to the king, "The report I heard in my own country about your words and about your wisdom is true.
111Kg 10:7 But I didn't believe the reports until I came and saw with my own eyes. Indeed, I was not even told half. Your wisdom and prosperity far exceed the report I heard.
111Kg 10:8 How happy are your men. How happy are these servants of yours, who always stand in your presence hearing your wisdom.
111Kg 10:9 May the LORD your God be praised! He delighted in you and put you on the throne of Israel, because of the LORD's eternal love for Israel. He has made you king to carry out justice and righteousness."
111Kg 10:10 Then she gave the king four and a half tons of gold, a great quantity of spices, and precious stones. Never again did such a quantity of spices arrive as those the queen of Sheba gave to King Solomon.
111Kg 10:11 In addition, Hiram's fleet that carried gold from Ophir brought from Ophir a large quantity of almug wood and precious stones.
111Kg 10:12 The king made the almug wood into steps for the LORD's temple and the king's palace and into harps and lyres for the singers. Never [before] had such almug wood come, and [the like] has not been seen [again] even to this very day.
111Kg 10:13 King Solomon gave the queen of Sheba her every desire-- whatever she asked-- besides what he had given her out of his royal bounty. Then she, along with her servants, returned to her own country.
111Kg 10:14 The weight of gold that came to Solomon annually was 25 tons,
111Kg 10:15 besides what came from merchants, traders' merchandise, and all the Arabian kings and governors of the land.
111Kg 10:16 King Solomon made 200 large shields of hammered gold; 15 pounds of gold went into each shield.
111Kg 10:17 He made 300 small shields of hammered gold; about four pounds of gold went into each shield. The king put them in the House of the Forest of Lebanon.
111Kg 10:18 The king also made a large ivory throne and overlaid it with fine gold.
111Kg 10:19 The throne had six steps; there was a rounded top at the back of the throne, armrests on either side of the seat, and two lions standing beside the armrests.
111Kg 10:20 Twelve lions were standing there on the six steps, one at each end. Nothing like it had ever been made in any other kingdom.
111Kg 10:21 All of King Solomon's drinking cups were gold, and all the utensils of the House of the Forest of Lebanon were pure gold. There was no silver, since it was considered as nothing in Solomon's time,
111Kg 10:22 for the king had ships of Tarshish at sea with Hiram's fleet, and once every three years the ships of Tarshish would arrive bearing gold, silver, ivory, apes, and peacocks.
111Kg 10:23 King Solomon surpassed all the kings of the world in riches and in wisdom.
111Kg 10:24 The whole world wanted an audience with Solomon to hear the wisdom that God had put in his heart.
111Kg 10:25 Every man would bring his annual tribute: items of silver and gold, clothing, weapons, spices, and horses and mules.
111Kg 10:26 Solomon accumulated 1,400 chariots and 12,000 horsemen and stationed them in the chariot cities and with the king in Jerusalem.
111Kg 10:27 The king made silver as common in Jerusalem as stones, and he made cedar as abundant as sycamore in the Judean foothills.
111Kg 10:28 Solomon's horses were imported from Egypt and Kue. The king's traders bought them from Kue at the going price.
111Kg 10:29 A chariot was imported from Egypt for 15 pounds [of silver], and a horse for about four pounds. In the same way, they exported them to all the kings of the Hittites and to the kings of Aram through their agents.
111Kg 11:1 King Solomon loved many foreign women in addition to Pharaoh's daughter: Moabite, Ammonite, Edomite, Sidonian, and Hittite women
111Kg 11:2 from the nations that the LORD had told the Israelites about, "Do not intermarry with them, and they must not intermarry with you, because they will turn you away [from Me] to their gods." Solomon was deeply attached to these women and loved [them].
111Kg 11:3 He had 700 wives who were princesses and 300 concubines, and they turned his heart away [from the LORD].
111Kg 11:4 When Solomon was old, his wives seduced him [to follow] other gods. His heart was not completely with the LORD his God, as his father David's heart had been.
111Kg 11:5 Solomon followed Ashtoreth, the goddess of the Sidonians, and Milcom, the detestable idol of the Ammonites.
111Kg 11:6 Solomon did what was evil in the LORD's sight, and unlike his father David, he did not completely follow the LORD.
111Kg 11:7 At that time, Solomon built a high place for Chemosh, the detestable idol of Moab, and for Milcom, the detestable idol of the Ammonites on the hill across from Jerusalem.
111Kg 11:8 He did the same for all his foreign wives, who were burning incense and offering sacrifices to their gods.
111Kg 11:9 The LORD was angry with Solomon, because his heart had turned away from the LORD God of Israel, who had appeared to him twice.
111Kg 11:10 He had commanded him about this, so that he would not follow other gods, but Solomon did not do what the LORD had commanded.
111Kg 11:11 Then the LORD said to Solomon, "Since you have done this and did not keep My covenant and My statutes, which I commanded you, I will tear the kingdom away from you and give it to your servant.
111Kg 11:12 However, I will not do it during your lifetime because of your father David; I will tear it out of your son's hand.
111Kg 11:13 Yet, I will not tear the entire kingdom away from him. I will give one tribe to your son because of my servant David and because of Jerusalem that I chose."
111Kg 11:14 So the LORD raised up Hadad the Edomite as an enemy against Solomon. He was of the royal family in Edom.
111Kg 11:15 Earlier, when David was in Edom, Joab, the commander of the army, had gone to bury the dead and had struck down every male in Edom.
111Kg 11:16 For Joab and all Israel had remained there six months, until he had killed every male in Edom.
111Kg 11:17 Hadad fled to Egypt, along with some Edomites from his father's servants. At the time Hadad was a small boy.
111Kg 11:18 Hadad and his men set out from Midian and went to Paran. They took men with them from Paran and went to Egypt, to Pharaoh king of Egypt, who gave Hadad a house, ordered that he [be given] food, and gave him land.
111Kg 11:19 Pharaoh liked Hadad so much that he gave him a wife, the sister of his own wife, Queen Tahpenes.
111Kg 11:20 Tahpenes' sister gave birth to Hadad's son Genubath. Tahpenes [herself] weaned him in Pharaoh's palace, and Genubath [lived] there along with Pharaoh's sons.
111Kg 11:21 When Hadad heard in Egypt that David rested with his fathers and that Joab, the commander of the army, was dead, Hadad said to Pharaoh, "Let me leave, so I can go to my own country."
111Kg 11:22 But Pharaoh asked him, "What do you lack here with me for you to want to go back to your own country?" "Nothing," he replied, "but please let me leave."
111Kg 11:23 God raised up Rezon son of Eliada as an enemy against Solomon. Rezon had fled from his master Hadadezer king of Zobah
111Kg 11:24 and gathered men to himself. He became captain of a raiding party when David killed the Zobaites. He went to Damascus, lived there, and became king in Damascus.
111Kg 11:25 Rezon was Israel's enemy throughout Solomon's reign, adding to the trouble Hadad [had caused]. He ruled over Aram, but he loathed Israel.
111Kg 11:26 Now Solomon's servant, Jeroboam son of Nebat, was an Ephraimite from Zeredah. His widowed mother's name was Zeruah. Jeroboam rebelled against Solomon,
111Kg 11:27 and this is the reason he rebelled against the king: Solomon had built the supporting terraces [and] repaired the opening in the wall of the city of his father David.
111Kg 11:28 Now the man Jeroboam was capable, and Solomon noticed the young man because he was getting things done. So he appointed him over the entire labor force of the house of Joseph.
111Kg 11:29 During that time, the prophet Ahijah the Shilonite met Jeroboam on the road as Jeroboam came out of Jerusalem. Now Ahijah had wrapped himself with a new cloak, and the two of them were alone in the open field.
111Kg 11:30 Then Ahijah took hold of the new cloak he had on, tore it into 12 pieces,
111Kg 11:31 and said to Jeroboam, "Take 10 pieces for yourself, for this is what the LORD God of Israel says: 'I am about to tear the kingdom out of Solomon's hand. I will give you 10 tribes,
111Kg 11:32 but one tribe will remain his because of my servant David and because of Jerusalem, the city I chose out of all the tribes of Israel.
111Kg 11:33 For they have abandoned Me; they have bowed the knee to Ashtoreth, the goddess of the Sidonians, to Chemosh, the god of Moab, and to Milcom, the god of the Ammonites. They have not walked in My ways to do right in My eyes and to carry out My statutes and My judgments as his father David did.
111Kg 11:34 " 'However, I will not take the whole kingdom from his hand but will let him be ruler all the days of his life because of My servant David, whom I chose and who kept My commandments and My statutes.
111Kg 11:35 I will take 10 tribes of the kingdom from his son's hand and give them to you.
111Kg 11:36 I will give one tribe to his son, so that My servant David will always have a lamp before Me in Jerusalem, the city I chose for Myself to put My name there.
111Kg 11:37 I will appoint you, and you will reign as king over all you want, and you will be king over Israel.
111Kg 11:38 " 'After that, if you obey all I command you, walk in My ways, and do what is right in My sight in order to keep My statutes and My commandments as My servant David did, I will be with you. I will build you a lasting dynasty just as I built for David, and I will give you Israel.
111Kg 11:39 I will humble David's descendants, because of [their unfaithfulness], but not forever.'"
111Kg 11:40 Therefore, Solomon tried to kill Jeroboam, but he fled to Egypt, to Shishak king of Egypt, where he remained until Solomon's death.
111Kg 11:41 The rest of the events of Solomon's [reign], along with all his accomplishments and his wisdom, are written about in the Book of Solomon's Events.
111Kg 11:42 The length of Solomon's reign in Jerusalem over all Israel totaled 40 years.
111Kg 11:43 Solomon rested with his fathers and was buried in the city of his father David. His son Rehoboam became king in his place.
111Kg 12:1 Then Rehoboam went to Shechem, for all Israel had gone to Shechem to make him king.
111Kg 12:2 When Jeroboam son of Nebat heard [about it], for he was still in Egypt where he had fled from King Solomon's presence, Jeroboam stayed in Egypt.
111Kg 12:3 They summoned him, and Jeroboam and the whole assembly of Israel came and spoke to Rehoboam:
111Kg 12:4 "Your father made our yoke harsh. You, therefore, lighten your father's harsh service and the heavy yoke he put on us, and we will serve you."
111Kg 12:5 Rehoboam replied, "Go home for three days and then return to me." So the people left.
111Kg 12:6 Then King Rehoboam consulted with the elders who had served his father Solomon when he was alive, asking, "How do you advise me to respond to these people?"
111Kg 12:7 They replied, "Today if you will be a servant to these people and serve them, and if you respond to them by speaking kind words to them, they will be your servants forever."
111Kg 12:8 But he rejected the advice of the elders who had advised him and consulted with the young men who had grown up with him and served him.
111Kg 12:9 He asked them, "What message do you advise that we send back to these people who said to me, 'Lighten the yoke your father put on us'?"
111Kg 12:10 Then the young men who had grown up with him told him, "This is what you should say to these people who said to you, 'Your father made our yoke heavy, but you, make it lighter on us!' This is what you should tell them: 'My little finger is thicker than my father's loins!
111Kg 12:11 Although my father burdened you with a heavy yoke, I will add to your yoke; my father disciplined you with whips, but I will discipline you with barbed whips.'"
111Kg 12:12 So Jeroboam and all the people came to Rehoboam on the third day, as the king had ordered: "Return to me on the third day."
111Kg 12:13 Then the king answered the people harshly. He rejected the advice the elders had given him
111Kg 12:14 and spoke to them according to the young men's advice: "My father made your yoke heavy, but I will add to your yoke; my father disciplined you with whips, but I will discipline you with barbed whips."
111Kg 12:15 The king did not listen to the people, because the turn of events came from the LORD to carry out His word, which the LORD had spoken through Ahijah the Shilonite to Jeroboam son of Nebat.
111Kg 12:16 When all Israel saw that the king had not listened to them, the people answered him: What portion do we have in David? We have no inheritance in the son of Jesse. Israel, return to your tents; David, now look after your own house! So Israel went to their tents,
111Kg 12:17 but Rehoboam reigned over the Israelites living in the cities of Judah.
111Kg 12:18 Then King Rehoboam sent Adoram, who was in charge of forced labor, but all Israel stoned him to death. King Rehoboam managed to get into the chariot and flee to Jerusalem.
111Kg 12:19 Israel is in rebellion against the house of David until today.
111Kg 12:20 When all Israel heard that Jeroboam had come back, they summoned him to the assembly and made him king over all Israel. No one followed the house of David except the tribe of Judah alone.
111Kg 12:21 When Rehoboam arrived in Jerusalem, he mobilized 180,000 choice warriors from the entire house of Judah and the tribe of Benjamin to fight against the house of Israel to restore the kingdom to Rehoboam son of Solomon.
111Kg 12:22 But a revelation from God came to Shemaiah, the man of God:
111Kg 12:23 "Say to Rehoboam son of Solomon, king of Judah, to the whole house of Judah and Benjamin, and to the rest of the people,
111Kg 12:24 'This is what the LORD says: You are not to march up and fight against your brothers, the Israelites. Each of you must return home, for I have done this.' " So they listened to what the LORD said and went back as He had told them.
111Kg 12:25 Jeroboam built Shechem in the hill country of Ephraim and lived there. From there he went out and built Penuel.
111Kg 12:26 Jeroboam said to himself, "[The way things are going] now, the kingdom might return to the house of David.
111Kg 12:27 If these people regularly go to offer sacrifices in the LORD's temple in Jerusalem, the heart of these people will return to their lord, Rehoboam king of Judah. They will murder me and go back to the king of Judah."
111Kg 12:28 So the king sought advice. Then he made two gold calves, and he said to the people, "Going to Jerusalem is too difficult for you. Israel, here is your God who brought you out of the land of Egypt."
111Kg 12:29 He set up one in Bethel, and put the other in Dan.
111Kg 12:30 This led to sin; the people walked [in procession] before one of the calves all the way to Dan.
111Kg 12:31 Jeroboam also built shrines on the high places and set up priests from every class of people who were not Levites.
111Kg 12:32 Jeroboam made a festival in the eighth month on the fifteenth day of the month, like the festival in Judah. He offered sacrifices on the altar; he made this offering in Bethel to sacrifice to the calves he had set up. He also stationed in Bethel the priests for the high places he had set up.
111Kg 12:33 He offered sacrifices on the altar he had set up in Bethel on the fifteenth day of the eighth month, the month he had decided on his own. He made a festival for the Israelites, offered sacrifices on the altar, and burned incense.
111Kg 13:1 A man of God came from Judah to Bethel by a revelation from the LORD while Jeroboam was standing beside the altar to burn incense.
111Kg 13:2 The man of God cried out against the altar by a revelation from the LORD: "Altar, altar, this is what the LORD says, 'A son will be born to the house of David, named Josiah, and he will sacrifice on you the priests of the high places who are burning incense on you. Human bones will be burned on you.'"
111Kg 13:3 He gave a sign that day. He said, "This is the sign that the LORD has spoken: 'The altar will now be ripped apart, and the ashes that are on it will be spilled out.'"
111Kg 13:4 When the king heard the word that the man of God had cried out against the altar at Bethel, Jeroboam stretched out his hand from the altar and said, "Arrest him!" But the hand he stretched out against him withered, and he could not pull it back to himself.
111Kg 13:5 The altar was ripped apart, and the ashes spilled off the altar, according to the sign that the man of God had given by the word of the LORD.
111Kg 13:6 Then the king responded to the man of God, "Please plead for the favor of the LORD your God and pray for me so that my hand may be restored to me." So the man of God pleaded for the favor of the LORD, and the king's hand was restored to him and became as it had been at first.
111Kg 13:7 Then the king declared to the man of God, "Come home with me, refresh yourself, and I'll give you a reward."
111Kg 13:8 But the man of God replied, "If you were to give me half your house, I still wouldn't go with you, and I wouldn't eat bread or drink water in this place,
111Kg 13:9 for this is what I was commanded by the word of the LORD: 'You must not eat bread or drink water or go back the way you came.'"
111Kg 13:10 So he went another way; he did not go back by the way he had come to Bethel.
111Kg 13:11 Now a certain old prophet was living in Bethel. His son came and told him all the deeds that the man of God had done that day in Bethel. His sons also told their father the words that he had spoken to the king.
111Kg 13:12 Then their father said to them, "Which way did he go?" His sons had seen the way taken by the man of God who had come from Judah.
111Kg 13:13 Then he said to his sons, "Saddle the donkey for me." So they saddled the donkey for him, and he got on it.
111Kg 13:14 He followed the man of God and found him sitting under an oak tree. He asked him, "Are you the man of God who came from Judah?" "I am," he said.
111Kg 13:15 Then he said to him, "Come home with me and eat bread."
111Kg 13:16 But he answered, "I cannot go back with you, eat bread, or drink water with you in this place,
111Kg 13:17 for a message came to me by the word of the LORD: 'You must not eat bread or drink water there or go back by the way you came.'"
111Kg 13:18 He said to him, "I am also a prophet like you. An angel spoke to me by the word of the LORD: 'Bring him back with you to your house so that he may eat bread and drink water.' " The old prophet deceived him,
111Kg 13:19 and the man of God went back with him, ate bread in his house, and drank water.
111Kg 13:20 While they were sitting at the table, the word of the LORD came to the prophet who had brought him back,
111Kg 13:21 and the prophet cried out to the man of God who had come from Judah, "This is what the LORD says: 'Because you rebelled against the command of the LORD and did not keep the commandment that the LORD your God commanded you,
111Kg 13:22 but you went back and ate bread and drank water in the place that He said to you: Do not eat bread and do not drink water, your corpse will never reach the grave of your fathers.'"
111Kg 13:23 So after he had eaten bread and after he had drunk, the old prophet saddled the donkey for the prophet he had brought back.
111Kg 13:24 When he left, a lion met him along the way and killed him. His corpse was thrown on the road, and the donkey was standing beside it; the lion was standing beside the corpse too.
111Kg 13:25 There were men passing by who saw the corpse thrown on the road and the lion standing beside it, and they went and spoke [about it] in the city where the old prophet lived.
111Kg 13:26 When the prophet who had brought him back from his way heard [about it], he said, "He is the man of God who disobeyed the command of the LORD. The LORD has given him to the lion, and it has mauled him and killed him, according to the word of the LORD that He spoke to him."
111Kg 13:27 Then the old prophet instructed his sons, "Saddle the donkey for me." They saddled it,
111Kg 13:28 and he went and found the corpse of the man of God thrown on the road with the donkey and the lion standing beside the corpse. The lion had not eaten the corpse or mauled the donkey.
111Kg 13:29 So the prophet lifted the corpse of the man of God and laid it on the donkey and brought it back. The old prophet came into to the city to mourn and to bury him.
111Kg 13:30 Then he laid the corpse in his own grave, and they mourned over him: "Oh, my brother!"
111Kg 13:31 After he had buried him, he said to his sons, "When I die, you must bury me in the grave where the man of God is buried; lay my bones beside his bones,
111Kg 13:32 for the word that he cried out by a revelation from the LORD against the altar in Bethel and against all the shrines of the high places in the cities of Samaria is certain to happen."
111Kg 13:33 After all this Jeroboam did not repent of his evil way but again set up priests from every class of people for the high places. Whoever so desired it, he ordained, and they became priests of the high places.
111Kg 13:34 For the house of Jeroboam, this was the sin that caused it to be wiped out and annihilated from the face of the earth.
111Kg 14:1 At that time Abijah son of Jeroboam became sick.
111Kg 14:2 Jeroboam said to his wife, "Go disguise yourself, so they won't know that you're Jeroboam's wife, and go to Shiloh. Ahijah the prophet is there; it was he who told about me becoming king over this people.
111Kg 14:3 Take with you 10 loaves of bread, some cakes, and a jar of honey, and go to him. He will tell you what will happen to the boy."
111Kg 14:4 Jeroboam's wife did that: she went to Shiloh and arrived at Ahijah's house. Ahijah could not see; his gaze was fixed due to his age.
111Kg 14:5 But the LORD had said to Ahijah, "Jeroboam's wife is coming soon to ask you about her son, for he is sick. You are to say such and such to her. When she arrives, she will be disguised."
111Kg 14:6 When Ahijah heard the sound of her feet entering the door, he said, "Come in, wife of Jeroboam! Why are you disguised? I have bad news for you.
111Kg 14:7 Go tell Jeroboam, 'This is what the LORD God of Israel says: I raised you up from among the people, appointed you ruler over My people Israel,
111Kg 14:8 tore the kingdom away from the house of David, and gave it to you. But you were not like My servant David, who kept My commandments and followed Me with all of his heart, doing only what is right in My eyes.
111Kg 14:9 You behaved more wickedly than all who were before you. In order to provoke Me, you have proceeded to make for yourself other gods and cast images, but you have flung Me behind your back.
111Kg 14:10 Because of all this, I am about to bring disaster on the house of Jeroboam: I will eliminate all of Jeroboam's males, both slave and free, in Israel; I will sweep away the house of Jeroboam as one sweeps away dung until it is all gone!
111Kg 14:11 Anyone who belongs to Jeroboam and dies in the city, the dogs will eat, and anyone who dies in the field, the birds of the sky will eat, for the LORD has said it!'
111Kg 14:12 "As for you, get up and go to your house. When your feet enter the city, the boy will die.
111Kg 14:13 All Israel will mourn for him and bury him, for this one alone out of Jeroboam's [sons] will come to the grave, because in him [alone] out of the house of Jeroboam something was found pleasing to the LORD God of Israel.
111Kg 14:14 The LORD will raise up for Himself a king over Israel, who will eliminate the house of Jeroboam. This is the day, yes, even today!
111Kg 14:15 For the LORD will strike Israel [and the people will shake] as a reed shakes in water. He will uproot Israel from this good soil that He gave to their forefathers. He will scatter them beyond the Euphrates because they made their Asherah poles, provoking the LORD.
111Kg 14:16 He will give up Israel, because of Jeroboam's sins that he committed and caused Israel to commit."
111Kg 14:17 Then Jeroboam's wife got up and left and went to Tirzah. As she was crossing the threshold of the house, the boy died.
111Kg 14:18 He was buried, and all Israel mourned for him, according to the word of the LORD He had spoken through His servant Ahijah the prophet.
111Kg 14:19 As for the rest of the events of Jeroboam's [reign], how he waged war and how he reigned, note that they are written about in the Historical Record of Israel's Kings.
111Kg 14:20 The length of Jeroboam's reign was 22 years. He rested with his fathers, and his son Nadab became king in his place.
111Kg 14:21 Now Rehoboam, Solomon's son, reigned in Judah. Rehoboam was 41 years old when he became king; he reigned 17 years in Jerusalem, the city the LORD had chosen from all the tribes of Israel to put His name. Rehoboam's mother's name was Naamah the Ammonite.
111Kg 14:22 Judah did what was evil in the LORD's eyes. They provoked Him to jealous anger more than all that their ancestors had done with the sins they committed.
111Kg 14:23 They also built for themselves high places, sacred pillars, and Asherah poles on every high hill and under every green tree;
111Kg 14:24 there were even male shrine prostitutes in the land. They imitated all the abominations of the nations the LORD had dispossessed before the Israelites.
111Kg 14:25 In the fifth year of King Rehoboam, Shishak king of Egypt went to war against Jerusalem.
111Kg 14:26 He seized the treasuries of the LORD's temple and the treasuries of the royal palace. He took everything. He took all the gold shields that Solomon had made.
111Kg 14:27 King Rehoboam made bronze shields in their place and committed them into the care of the captains of the royal escortswho guarded the entrance to the king's palace.
111Kg 14:28 Whenever the king entered the LORD's temple, the royal escorts would carry the shields, then they would take them back to the royal escorts' armory.
111Kg 14:29 The rest of the events of Rehoboam's [reign], along with all his accomplishments, are written about in the Historical Record of Judah's Kings.
111Kg 14:30 There was war between Rehoboam and Jeroboam throughout their reigns.
111Kg 14:31 Rehoboam rested with his fathers and was buried with his fathers in the city of David. His mother's name was Naamah the Ammonite. His son Abijam became king in his place.
111Kg 15:1 In the eighteenth year of [Israel's] King Jeroboam son of Nebat, Abijam became king over Judah;
111Kg 15:2 he reigned three years in Jerusalem. His mother's name was Maacah daughter of Abishalom.
111Kg 15:3 Abijam walked in all the sins his father had done before him, and he was not completely devoted to the LORD his God as his ancestor David had been.
111Kg 15:4 But because of David, the LORD his God gave him a lamp in Jerusalem to raise up his son after him and to establish Jerusalem
111Kg 15:5 because David did what was right in the LORD's eyes, and he did not turn aside from anything He had commanded him all the days of his life, except in the matter of Uriah the Hittite.
111Kg 15:6 There had been war between Rehoboam and Jeroboam all the days of Rehoboam's life.
111Kg 15:7 The rest of the events of Abijam's [reign], along with all his accomplishments, are written about in the Historical Record of Judah's Kings. There was also war between Abijam and Jeroboam.
111Kg 15:8 Abijam rested with his fathers and was buried in the city of David. His son Asa became king in his place.
111Kg 15:9 In the twentieth year of Israel's King Jeroboam, Asa became king of Judah;
111Kg 15:10 he reigned 41 years in Jerusalem. His grandmother's name was Maacah daughter of Abishalom.
111Kg 15:11 Asa did what was right in the LORD's eyes, as his ancestor David had done.
111Kg 15:12 He banished the male shrine prostitutes from the land and removed all of the idols that his fathers had made.
111Kg 15:13 He also removed his grandmother Maacah from being queen mother because she had made an obscene image of Asherah. Asa chopped down her obscene image and burned it in the Kidron Valley.
111Kg 15:14 The high places were not taken away; but Asa's heart was completely with the LORD his entire life.
111Kg 15:15 He brought his father's consecrated gifts and his own consecrated gifts into the LORD's temple: silver, gold, and utensils.
111Kg 15:16 There was war between Asa and Baasha king of Israel throughout their reigns.
111Kg 15:17 Israel's King Baasha went to war against Judah. He built Ramah in order to deny anyone access to Judah's King Asa.
111Kg 15:18 So Asa withdrew all the silver and gold that remained in the treasuries of the LORD's temple and the treasuries of the royal palace and put it into the hands of his servants. Then King Asa sent them to Ben-hadad son of Tabrimmon son of Hezion king of Aram who lived in Damascus, saying,
111Kg 15:19 "There is a treaty between me and you, between my father and your father. Look, I have sent you a gift of silver and gold. Go and break your treaty with Baasha king of Israel so that he will withdraw from me."
111Kg 15:20 Ben-hadad listened to King Asa and sent the commanders of his armies against the cities of Israel. He attacked Ijon, Dan, Abel-beth-maacah, all Chinneroth, and the whole land of Naphtali.
111Kg 15:21 When Baasha heard [about it], he quit building Ramah and stayed in Tirzah.
111Kg 15:22 Then King Asa gave a command to everyone without exception in Judah, and they carried away the stones of Ramah and the timbers Baasha had built it with. Then King Asa built Geba of Benjamin and Mizpah with them.
111Kg 15:23 The rest of all the events of Asa's [reign], along with all his might, all his accomplishments, and the cities he built, are written about in the Historical Record of Judah's Kings. But in his old age he developed a disease in his feet.
111Kg 15:24 Then Asa rested with his fathers and was buried in the city of his forefather David. His son Jehoshaphat became king in his place.
111Kg 15:25 Nadab son of Jeroboam became king over Israel in the second year of Judah's King Asa; he reigned over Israel two years.
111Kg 15:26 Nadab did what was evil in the LORD's sight and followed the example of his father and the sin he had caused Israel to commit.
111Kg 15:27 Then Baasha son of Ahijah of the house of Issachar conspired against Nadab, and Baasha struck him down at Gibbethon of the Philistines while Nadab and all Israel were besieging Gibbethon.
111Kg 15:28 In the third year of Judah's King Asa, Baasha killed Nadab and reigned in his place.
111Kg 15:29 When Baasha became king, he struck down the entire house of Jeroboam. He did not leave Jeroboam anyone alive until he had destroyed his family according to the word of the LORD He had spoken through His servant Ahijah the Shilonite.
111Kg 15:30 This was because of Jeroboam's sins he had committed and had caused Israel to commit in the provocation he had provoked the LORD God of Israel with.
111Kg 15:31 The rest of the events of Nadab's [reign], along with all his accomplishments, are written about in the Historical Record of Israel's Kings.
111Kg 15:32 There was war between Asa and Baasha king of Israel throughout their reigns.
111Kg 15:33 In the third year of Judah's King Asa, Baasha son of Ahijah became king over all Israel at Tirzah; [he reigned] 24 years.
111Kg 15:34 He did what was evil in the LORD's sight and followed the example of Jeroboam and the sin he had caused Israel to commit.
111Kg 16:1 Now the word of the LORD came to Jehu son of Hanani against Baasha:
111Kg 16:2 "Because I raised you up from the dust and made you ruler over My people Israel, but you have walked in the way of Jeroboam and have caused My people Israel to sin, provoking Me with their sins,
111Kg 16:3 take note: I will sweep away Baasha and his house, and I will make your house like the house of Jeroboam son of Nebat:
111Kg 16:4 Anyone who belongs to Baasha and dies in the city, the dogs will eat, and anyone who is his and dies in the field, the birds of the sky will eat.
111Kg 16:5 The rest of the events of Baasha's [reign], along with all his accomplishments and might, are written about in the Historical Record of Israel's Kings.
111Kg 16:6 Baasha rested with his fathers and was buried in Tirzah. His son Elah became king in his place.
111Kg 16:7 Through the prophet Jehu son of Hanani the word of the LORD also came against Baasha and against his house because of all the evil he had done in the LORD's sight, provoking Him with the work of his hands and being like the house of Jeroboam, and because Baasha had struck down the house of Jeroboam.
111Kg 16:8 In the twenty-sixth year of Judah's King Asa, Elah son of Baasha became king over Israel in Tirzah; [he reigned] two years.
111Kg 16:9 His servant Zimri, commander of half his chariots, conspired against him while Elah was in Tirzah drinking himself drunk in the house of Arza, who was in charge of the household at Tirzah.
111Kg 16:10 In the twenty-seventh year of Judah's King Asa, Zimri went in, struck Elah down, and killed him. Then Zimri became king in his place.
111Kg 16:11 When he became king, as soon as he was seated on his throne, Zimri struck down the entire house of Baasha. He did not leave him a single male, whether of his kinsmen or his friends.
111Kg 16:12 So Zimri exterminated the entire house of Baasha, according to the word of the LORD He had spoken against Baasha through Jehu the prophet,
111Kg 16:13 because of all the sins of Baasha and the sins of his son Elah, which they committed and caused Israel to commit, provoking the LORD God of Israel with their worthless idols.
111Kg 16:14 The rest of the events of Elah's [reign], along with all his accomplishments, are written about in the Historical Record of Israel's Kings.
111Kg 16:15 In the twenty-seventh year of Judah's King Asa, Zimri became king for seven days in Tirzah. Now the troops were encamped against Gibbethon of the Philistines.
111Kg 16:16 When the encamped troops heard that Zimri had not only conspired but had also struck down the king, then all Israel made Omri, the army commander, king over Israel that very day in the camp.
111Kg 16:17 Omri along with all Israel marched up from Gibbethon and besieged Tirzah.
111Kg 16:18 When Zimri saw that the city was captured, he entered the citadel of the royal palace and burned down the royal palace over himself. He died
111Kg 16:19 because of his sin he committed by doing what was evil in the LORD's sight and by following the example of Jeroboam and the sin he caused Israel to commit.
111Kg 16:20 The rest of the events of Zimri's [reign], along with the conspiracy that he instigated, are written about in the Historical Record of Israel's Kings.
111Kg 16:21 At that time the people of Israel were split in half: half the people followed Tibni son of Ginath, to make him king, and half followed Omri.
111Kg 16:22 However, the people who followed Omri proved stronger than those who followed Tibni son of Ginath. So Tibni died and Omri became king.
111Kg 16:23 In the thirty-first year of Judah's King Asa, Omri became king over Israel; [he reigned] 12 years. He reigned six years in Tirzah,
111Kg 16:24 then he bought the hill of Samaria from Shemer for 150 pounds of silver, and he built up the hill. He named the city he built Samaria based on the name Shemer, the owner of the hill.
111Kg 16:25 Omri did what was evil in the LORD's sight; he did more evil than all who were before him.
111Kg 16:26 He followed the example of Jeroboam son of Nebat and the sins he caused Israel to commit, provoking the LORD God of Israel with their worthless idols.
111Kg 16:27 The rest of the events of Omri's [reign], along with his accomplishments and the might he exercised, are written about in the Historical Record of Israel's Kings.
111Kg 16:28 Omri rested with his fathers and was buried in Samaria. His son Ahab became king in his place.
111Kg 16:29 Ahab son of Omri became king over Israel in the thirty-eighth year of Judah's King Asa; Ahab son of Omri reigned over Israel in Samaria 22 years.
111Kg 16:30 But Ahab son of Omri did what was evil in the LORD's sight more than all who were before him.
111Kg 16:31 Then, as if following the sin of Jeroboam son of Nebat were a trivial matter, he married Jezebel, the daughter of Ethbaal king of the Sidonians, and then proceeded to serve Baal and worship him.
111Kg 16:32 He set up an altar for Baal in the temple of Baal that he had built in Samaria.
111Kg 16:33 Ahab also made an Asherah pole. Ahab did more to provoke the LORD God of Israel than all the kings of Israel who were before him.
111Kg 16:34 During his reign, Hiel the Bethelite built Jericho. At the cost of Abiram his firstborn, he laid its foundation, and at the cost of Segub his youngest, he set up its gates, according to the word of the LORD He had spoken through Joshua son of Nun.
111Kg 17:1 Now Elijah the Tishbite, from the Gilead settlers, said to Ahab, "As the LORD God of Israel lives, I stand before Him, and there will be no dew or rain during these years except by my command!"
111Kg 17:2 Then a revelation from the LORD came to him:
111Kg 17:3 "Leave here, turn eastward, and hide yourself at the Wadi Cherith where it enters the Jordan.
111Kg 17:4 You are to drink from the wadi. I have commanded the ravens to provide for you there."
111Kg 17:5 So he did what the LORD commanded. Elijah left and lived by the Wadi Cherith where it enters the Jordan.
111Kg 17:6 The ravens kept bringing him bread and meat in the morning and in the evening, and he drank from the wadi.
111Kg 17:7 After a while, the wadi dried up because there had been no rain in the land.
111Kg 17:8 Then the word of the LORD came to him:
111Kg 17:9 "Get up, go to Zarephath that belongs to Sidon, and stay there. Look, I have commanded a woman who is a widow to provide for you there."
111Kg 17:10 So Elijah got up and went to Zarephath. When he arrived at the city gate, there was a widow woman gathering wood. Elijah called to her and said, "Please bring me a little water in a cup and let me drink."
111Kg 17:11 As she went to get it, he called to her and said, "Please bring me a piece of bread in your hand."
111Kg 17:12 But she said, "As the LORD your God lives, I don't have anything baked-- only a handful of flour in the jar and a bit of oil in the jug. Just now, I am gathering a couple of sticks in order to go prepare it for myself and my son so we can eat it and die."
111Kg 17:13 Then Elijah said to her, "Don't be afraid; go and do as you have said. Only make me a small loaf from it and bring it out to me. Afterwards, you may make some for yourself and your son,
111Kg 17:14 for this is what the LORD God of Israel says: 'The flour jar will not become empty and the oil jug will not run dry until the day the LORD sends rain on the surface of the land.'"
111Kg 17:15 So she proceeded to do according to the word of Elijah. She and he and her household ate for many days.
111Kg 17:16 The flour jar did not become empty, and the oil jug did not run dry, according to the word of the LORD He had spoken through Elijah.
111Kg 17:17 After this, the son of the woman who owned the house became ill. His illness became very severe until no breath remained in him.
111Kg 17:18 She said to Elijah, "Man of God, what do we have in common? Have you come to remind me of my guilt and to kill my son?"
111Kg 17:19 But Elijah said to her, "Give me your son." So he took him from her arms, brought him up to the upper room where he was staying, and laid him on his own bed.
111Kg 17:20 Then he cried out to the LORD and said, "My LORD God, have You also brought tragedy on the widow I am staying with by killing her son?"
111Kg 17:21 Then he stretched himself out over the boy three times. He cried out to the LORD and said, "My LORD God, please let this boy's life return to him!"
111Kg 17:22 So the LORD listened to Elijah's voice, and the boy's life returned to him, and he lived.
111Kg 17:23 Then Elijah took the boy, brought him down from the upper room into the house, and gave him to his mother. Elijah said, "Look, your son is alive."
111Kg 17:24 Then the woman said to Elijah, "Now I know you are a man of God and the LORD's word in your mouth is the truth."
111Kg 18:1 After a long time, the word of the LORD came to Elijah in the third year: "Go and present yourself to Ahab. I will send rain on the surface of the land."
111Kg 18:2 So Elijah went to present himself to Ahab. The famine was severe in Samaria.
111Kg 18:3 Ahab called for Obadiah, who was in charge of the palace. Obadiah was a man who greatly feared the LORD
111Kg 18:4 and took 100 prophets and hid them, 50 men to a cave, and provided them with food and water when Jezebel slaughtered the LORD's prophets.
111Kg 18:5 Ahab said to Obadiah, "Go throughout the land to every spring of water and to every wadi. Perhaps we'll find grass so we can keep the horses and mules alive and not have to destroy any cattle."
111Kg 18:6 They divided the land between them in order to cover it. Ahab went one way by himself, and Obadiah went the other way by himself.
111Kg 18:7 While Obadiah was [walking] along the road, Elijah suddenly met him. When Obadiah recognized him, he fell with his face [to the ground] and said, "Is it you, my lord Elijah?"
111Kg 18:8 "It is I," he replied. "Go tell your lord, 'Elijah is here!'"
111Kg 18:9 But Obadiah said, "What sin have I committed, that you are handing your servant over to Ahab to put me to death?
111Kg 18:10 As the LORD your God lives, there is no nation or kingdom where my lord has not sent someone to search for you. When they said, 'He is not here,' he made that kingdom or nation swear they had not found you.
111Kg 18:11 "Now you say, 'Go tell your lord, "Elijah is here!"'
111Kg 18:12 But when I leave you, the Spirit of the LORD may carry you off to some place I don't know. Then when I go report to Ahab and he doesn't find you, he will kill me. But [I], your servant, have feared the LORD from my youth.
111Kg 18:13 Wasn't it reported to my lord what I did when Jezebel slaughtered the LORD's prophets? I hid 100 of the prophets of the LORD, 50 men to a cave, and I provided them with food and water.
111Kg 18:14 Now you say, 'Go tell your lord, "Elijah is here!" ' He will kill me!"
111Kg 18:15 Then Elijah said, "As the LORD of Hosts lives, before whom I stand, today I will present myself to Ahab."
111Kg 18:16 Obadiah went to meet Ahab and report to him. Then Ahab went to meet Elijah.
111Kg 18:17 When Ahab saw Elijah, Ahab said to him, "Is that you, you destroyer of Israel?"
111Kg 18:18 He replied, "I have not destroyed Israel, but you and your father's house have, because you have abandoned the LORD's commandments and followed the Baals.
111Kg 18:19 Now summon all Israel to meet me at Mount Carmel, along with the 450 prophets of Baal and the 400 prophets of Asherah who eat at Jezebel's table."
111Kg 18:20 So Ahab summoned all the Israelites and gathered the prophets at Mount Carmel.
111Kg 18:21 Then Elijah approached all the people and said, "How long will you hesitate between two opinions? If Yahweh is God, follow Him. But if Baal, follow him." But the people didn't answer him a word.
111Kg 18:22 Then Elijah said to the people, "I am the only remaining prophet of the LORD, but Baal's prophets are 450 men.
111Kg 18:23 Let two bulls be given to us. They are to choose one bull for themselves, cut it in pieces, and place it on the wood but not light the fire. I will prepare the other bull and place it on the wood but not light the fire.
111Kg 18:24 Then you call on the name of your god, and I will call on the name of Yahweh. The God who answers with fire, He is God." All the people answered, "That [sounds] good."
111Kg 18:25 Then Elijah said to the prophets of Baal, "Since you are so numerous, choose for yourselves one bull and prepare it first. Then call on the name of your god but don't light the fire."
111Kg 18:26 So they took the bull that he gave them, prepared it, and called on the name of Baal from morning until noon, saying, "Baal, answer us!" But there was no sound; no one answered. Then they did their lame dance around the altar they had made.
111Kg 18:27 At noon Elijah mocked them. He said, "Shout loudly, for he's a god! Maybe he's thinking it over; maybe he has wandered away; or maybe he's on the road. Perhaps he's sleeping and will wake up!"
111Kg 18:28 They shouted loudly, and cut themselves with knives and spears, according to their custom, until blood gushed out on them.
111Kg 18:29 All afternoon, they kept on raving until the offering of the evening sacrifice, but there was no sound, no one answered, no one paid attention.
111Kg 18:30 Then Elijah said to all the people, "Come near me." So all the people approached him. Then he repaired the LORD's altar that had been torn down:
111Kg 18:31 Elijah took 12 stones-- according to the number of the tribes of the sons of Jacob, to whom the word of the LORD had come, saying, "Israel will be your name"--
111Kg 18:32 and he built an altar with the stones in the name of Yahweh. Then he made a trench around the altar large enough to hold about four gallons.
111Kg 18:33 Next, he arranged the wood, cut up the bull, and placed it on the wood. He said, "Fill four water pots with water and pour it on the offering to be burned and on the wood."
111Kg 18:34 Then he said, "A second time!" and they did it a second time. And then he said, "A third time!" and they did it a third time.
111Kg 18:35 So the water ran all around the altar; he even filled the trench with water.
111Kg 18:36 At the time for offering the [evening] sacrifice, Elijah the prophet approached [the altar] and said, "LORD God of Abraham, Isaac, and Israel, today let it be known that You are God in Israel and I am Your servant, and that at Your word I have done all these things.
111Kg 18:37 Answer me, LORD! Answer me so that this people will know that You, Yahweh, are God and that You have turned their hearts back."
111Kg 18:38 Then Yahweh's fire fell and consumed the burnt offering, the wood, the stones, and the dust, and it licked up the water that was in the trench.
111Kg 18:39 When all the people saw it, they fell facedown and said, "Yahweh, He is God! Yahweh, He is God!"
111Kg 18:40 Then Elijah ordered them, "Seize the prophets of Baal! Do not let even one of them escape." So they seized them, and Elijah brought them down to the Wadi Kishon and slaughtered them there.
111Kg 18:41 Elijah said to Ahab, "Go up, eat and drink, for there is the sound of a rainstorm."
111Kg 18:42 So Ahab went to eat and drink, but Elijah went up to the summit of Carmel. He bowed down to the ground and put his face between his knees.
111Kg 18:43 Then he said to his servant, "Go up and look toward the sea." So he went up, looked, and said, "There's nothing." Seven times Elijah said, "Go back."
111Kg 18:44 On the seventh time, he reported, "There's a cloud as small as a man's hand coming from the sea." Then Elijah said, "Go and tell Ahab, 'Get [your chariot] ready and go down so the rain doesn't stop you.'"
111Kg 18:45 In a little while, the sky grew dark with clouds and wind, and there was a downpour. So Ahab got in [his chariot] and went to Jezreel.
111Kg 18:46 The power of the LORD was on Elijah, and he tucked his mantle under his belt and ran ahead of Ahab to the entrance of Jezreel.
111Kg 19:1 Ahab told Jezebel everything that Elijah had done and how he had killed all the prophets with the sword.
111Kg 19:2 So Jezebel sent a messenger to Elijah, saying, "May the gods punish me and do so severely if I don't make your life like the life of one of them by this time tomorrow!"
111Kg 19:3 Then Elijah became afraid and immediately ran for his life. When he came to Beer-sheba that belonged to Judah, he left his servant there,
111Kg 19:4 but he went on a day's journey into the wilderness. He sat down under a broom tree and prayed that he might die. He said, "[I have had] enough! LORD, take my life, for I'm no better than my fathers."
111Kg 19:5 Then he lay down and slept under the broom tree. Suddenly, an angel touched him. The angel told him, "Get up and eat."
111Kg 19:6 Then he looked, and there at his head was a loaf of bread baked over hot stones and a jug of water. So he ate and drank and lay down again.
111Kg 19:7 Then the angel of the LORD returned a second time and touched him. He said, "Get up and eat, or the journey will be too much for you."
111Kg 19:8 So he got up, ate, and drank. Then on the strength from that food, he walked 40 days and 40 nights to Horeb, the mountain of God.
111Kg 19:9 He entered a cave there and spent the night. Then the word of the LORD came to him, and He said to him, "What are you doing here, Elijah?"
111Kg 19:10 He replied, "I have been very zealous for the LORD God of Hosts, but the Israelites have abandoned Your covenant, torn down Your altars, and killed Your prophets with the sword. I alone am left, and they are looking for me to take my life."
111Kg 19:11 Then He said, "Go out and stand on the mountain in the LORD's presence." At that moment, the LORD passed by. A great and mighty wind was tearing at the mountains and was shattering cliffs before the LORD, but the LORD was not in the wind. After the wind there was an earthquake, but the LORD was not in the earthquake.
111Kg 19:12 After the earthquake there was a fire, but the LORD was not in the fire. And after the fire there was a voice, a soft whisper.
111Kg 19:13 When Elijah heard [it], he wrapped his face in his mantle and went out and stood at the entrance of the cave. Suddenly, a voice came to him and said, "What are you doing here, Elijah?"
111Kg 19:14 "I have been very zealous for the LORD God of Hosts," he replied, "but the Israelites have abandoned Your covenant, torn down Your altars, and killed Your prophets with the sword. I alone am left, and they're looking for me to take my life."
111Kg 19:15 Then the LORD said to him, "Go and return by the way you came to the Wilderness of Damascus. When you arrive, you are to anoint Hazael as king over Aram.
111Kg 19:16 You are to anoint Jehu son of Nimshi as king over Israel and Elisha son of Shaphat from Abel-meholah as prophet in your place.
111Kg 19:17 Then Jehu will put to death whoever escapes the sword of Hazael, and Elisha will put to death whoever escapes the sword of Jehu.
111Kg 19:18 But I will leave 7,000 in Israel-- every knee that has not bowed to Baal and every mouth that has not kissed him."
111Kg 19:19 Elijah left there and found Elisha son of Shaphat as he was plowing. Twelve teams of oxen were in front of him, and he was with the twelfth team. Elijah walked by him and threw his mantle over him.
111Kg 19:20 Elisha left the oxen, ran to follow Elijah, and said, "Please let me kiss my father and mother, and then I will follow you." "Go on back," he replied, "for what have I done to you?"
111Kg 19:21 So he turned back from following him, took the team of oxen, and slaughtered them. With the oxen's wooden yoke and plow, he cooked the meat and gave it to the people, and they ate. Then he left, followed Elijah, and served him.
111Kg 20:1 Now Ben-hadad king of Aram assembled his entire army. Thirty-two kings, along with horses and chariotry, were with him. He marched up, besieged Samaria, and fought against it.
111Kg 20:2 He sent messengers into the city to Ahab king of Israel and said to him, "This is what Ben-hadad says:
111Kg 20:3 'Your silver and your gold are mine! And Your best wives and children are mine as well!'"
111Kg 20:4 Then the king of Israel answered, "Just as you say, my lord king: I am yours, along with all that I have."
111Kg 20:5 The messengers then returned and said, "This is what Ben-hadad says: 'I have sent [messengers] to you, saying: Your silver, your gold, your wives, and your children you are to give to me.
111Kg 20:6 But at this time tomorrow I will send my servants to you, and they will search your palace and your servants' houses. Whatever is precious to you, they will lay their hands on and take away.'"
111Kg 20:7 Then the king of Israel called for all the elders of the land and said, "Think it over and you will see that this one is only looking for trouble, for he demanded my wives, my children, my silver, and my gold, and I didn't turn him down."
111Kg 20:8 All the elders and all the people said to him, "Don't listen or agree."
111Kg 20:9 So he said to Ben-hadad's messengers, "Say to my lord the king, 'Everything you demanded of your servant the first time, I will do, but this thing I cannot do.' " So the messengers left and took word back to him.
111Kg 20:10 Then Ben-hadad sent [messengers] to him and said, "May the gods punish me and do so severely if Samaria's dust amounts to a handful for each of the people who follow me."
111Kg 20:11 The king of Israel answered, "Say this: 'Let not him who puts on his armor boast like the one who takes it off.'"
111Kg 20:12 When Ben-hadad heard this response, while he and the kings were drinking in the tents, he said to his servants, "Take [your] positions." So they took [their] positions against the city.
111Kg 20:13 A prophet came to Ahab king of Israel and said, "This is what the LORD says: 'Do you see this entire immense horde? Watch, I am handing it over to you today so that you may know that I am the LORD.'"
111Kg 20:14 Ahab asked, "By whom?" And the prophet said, "This is what the LORD says: 'By the young men of the provincial leaders.' " Then he asked, "Who is to start the battle?" He said, "You."
111Kg 20:15 So Ahab counted the young men of the provincial leaders, and there were 232. After them he counted all the Israelite troops: 7,000.
111Kg 20:16 They marched out at noon while Ben-hadad and the 32 kings who were helping him were getting drunk in the tents.
111Kg 20:17 The young men of the provincial leaders marched out first. Then Ben-hadad sent out scouts, and they reported to him, saying, "Men are marching out of Samaria."
111Kg 20:18 So he said, "If they have marched out in peace, take them alive, and if they have marched out for battle, take them alive."
111Kg 20:19 The young men of the provincial leaders and the army behind them marched out from the city,
111Kg 20:20 and each one struck down his opponent. So the Arameans fled and Israel pursued them, but Ben-hadad king of Aram escaped on a horse with the cavalry.
111Kg 20:21 Then the king of Israel marched out and attacked the cavalry and the chariotry. He inflicted a great slaughter on Aram.
111Kg 20:22 The prophet approached the king of Israel and said to him, "Go and strengthen yourself, then consider what you should do, for in the spring the king of Aram will march up against you."
111Kg 20:23 Now the king of Aram's servants said to him, "Their gods are gods of the hill country. That's why they were stronger than we. Instead, we should fight with them on the plain; then we will certainly be stronger than they.
111Kg 20:24 Also do this: remove each king from his position and appoint captains in their place.
111Kg 20:25 Raise another army for yourself like the army you lost-- horse for horse, chariot for chariot-- and let's fight with them on the plain; and we will certainly be stronger than they." The king listened to them and did so.
111Kg 20:26 In the spring, Ben-hadad mobilized the Arameans and went up to Aphek to battle Israel.
111Kg 20:27 The Israelites mobilized, gathered supplies, and went to fight them. The Israelites camped in front of them like two little flocks of goats, while the Arameans filled the landscape.
111Kg 20:28 Then the man of God approached and said to the king of Israel, "This is what the LORD says: 'Because the Arameans have said: The LORD is a god of the mountains and not a god of the valleys, I will hand over this entire immense horde to you. Then you will know that I am the LORD.'"
111Kg 20:29 They camped opposite each other for seven days. On the seventh day, the battle took place, and the Israelites struck down the Arameans-- 100,000 foot soldiers in one day.
111Kg 20:30 The ones who remained fled into the city of Aphek, and the wall fell on those 27,000 remaining men. Ben-hadad also fled and went into an inner room in the city.
111Kg 20:31 His servants said to him, "Consider this: we have heard that the kings of the house of Israel are kings [who show] special kindness. So let's put sackcloth around our waists and ropes around our heads, and let's go out to the king of Israel. Perhaps he will spare your life."
111Kg 20:32 So they dressed with sackcloth around their waists and ropes around their heads, went to the king of Israel, and said, "Your servant Ben-hadad says, 'Please spare my life.' " So he said, "Is he still alive? He is my brother."
111Kg 20:33 Now the men were looking for a sign of hope, so they quickly latched onto the hint and said, "Yes, your brother Ben-hadad." Then he said, "Go and bring him." So Ben-hadad came out to him, and Ahab had him come up into the chariot.
111Kg 20:34 Then Ben-hadad said to him, "The cities that my father took from your father I restore to you, and you may set up marketplaces for yourself in Damascus, like my father set up in Samaria." [Ahab responded],"On the basis of this treaty, I release you." So he made a treaty with him and released him.
111Kg 20:35 One of the sons of the prophets said to his fellow prophet by the word of the LORD, "Strike me!" But the man refused to strike him.
111Kg 20:36 He told him, "Because you did not listen to the voice of the LORD, mark my words: When you leave me, a lion will kill you." When he left him, a lion found him and killed him.
111Kg 20:37 The prophet found another man and said to him, "Strike me!" So the man struck him, inflicting a wound.
111Kg 20:38 Then the prophet went and waited for the king on the road. He disguised himself with a bandage over his eyes.
111Kg 20:39 As the king was passing by, he cried out to the king and said, "Your servant marched out into the midst of the battle. Suddenly, a man turned aside and brought someone to me and said, 'Guard this man! If he is ever missing, it will be your life in place of his life, or you will weigh out 75 pounds of silver.'
111Kg 20:40 But while your servant was busy here and there, he disappeared." The king of Israel said to him, "That will be your sentence; you yourself have decided it."
111Kg 20:41 He quickly removed the bandage from his eyes. The king of Israel recognized that he was one of the prophets.
111Kg 20:42 The prophet said to him, "This is what the LORD says: 'Because you released from your hand the man I had devoted to destruction, it will be your life in place of his life and your people in place of his people.'"
111Kg 20:43 The king of Israel left for home resentful and angry, and he entered Samaria.
111Kg 21:1 Some time passed after these events. Naboth the Jezreelite had a vineyard; it was in Jezreel next to the palace of Ahab king of Samaria.
111Kg 21:2 So Ahab spoke to Naboth, saying, "Give me your vineyard so I can have it for a vegetable garden, since it is right next to my palace. I will give you a better vineyard in its place, or if you prefer, I will give you its value in silver."
111Kg 21:3 But Naboth said to Ahab, "I will never give my fathers' inheritance to you."
111Kg 21:4 So Ahab went to his palace resentful and angry, because of what Naboth the Jezreelite had told him. He had said, "I will not give you my fathers' inheritance." He lay down on his bed, turned his face away, and didn't eat any food.
111Kg 21:5 Then his wife Jezebel came to him and said to him, "Why are you so upset that you refuse to eat?"
111Kg 21:6 "Because I spoke to Naboth the Jezreelite," he replied. "I told him: Give me your vineyard for silver, or if you wish, I will give you a vineyard in its place. But he said, 'I won't give you my vineyard!'"
111Kg 21:7 Then his wife Jezebel said to him, "Now, exercise your royal power over Israel. Get up, eat some food, and be happy. [For] I will give you the vineyard of Naboth the Jezreelite."
111Kg 21:8 So she wrote letters in Ahab's name and sealed them with his seal. She sent the letters to the elders and nobles who lived with Naboth in his city.
111Kg 21:9 In the letters, she wrote: Proclaim a fast and seat Naboth at the head of the people.
111Kg 21:10 Then seat two wicked men opposite him and have them testify against him, saying, "You have cursed God and king!" Then take him out and stone him to death.
111Kg 21:11 The men of his city, the elders and nobles who lived in his city, did as Jezebel had commanded them, as was written in the letters she had sent them.
111Kg 21:12 They proclaimed a fast and seated Naboth at the head of the people.
111Kg 21:13 The two wicked men came in and sat opposite him. Then the wicked men testified against Naboth in the presence of the people, saying, "Naboth has cursed God and king!" So they took him outside the city and stoned him to death with stones.
111Kg 21:14 Then they sent [word] to Jezebel, "Naboth has been stoned to death."
111Kg 21:15 When Jezebel heard that Naboth had been stoned to death, she said to Ahab, "Get up and take possession of the vineyard of Naboth the Jezreelite who refused to give it to you for silver, since Naboth isn't alive, but dead."
111Kg 21:16 When Ahab heard that Naboth was dead, he got up to go down to the vineyard of Naboth the Jezreelite to take possession of it.
111Kg 21:17 Then the word of the LORD came to Elijah the Tishbite:
111Kg 21:18 "Get up and go to meet Ahab king of Israel, who is in Samaria. You'll find him in Naboth's vineyard, where he has gone to take possession of it.
111Kg 21:19 Tell him, 'This is what the LORD says: Have you murdered and also taken possession?' Then tell him, 'This is what the LORD says: In the place where the dogs licked Naboth's blood, the dogs will also lick your blood!'"
111Kg 21:20 Ahab said to Elijah, "So, you have caught me, my enemy." He replied, "I have caught you because you devoted yourself to do what is evil in the LORD's sight.
111Kg 21:21 This is what the LORD says: 'I am about to bring disaster on you and will sweep away your descendants: I will eliminate all of Ahab's males, both slave and free, in Israel;
111Kg 21:22 I will make your house like the house of Jeroboam son of Nebat and like the house of Baasha son of Ahijah, because you have provoked [My] anger and caused Israel to sin.
111Kg 21:23 The LORD also speaks of Jezebel: The dogs will eat Jezebel in the plot of land at Jezreel:
111Kg 21:24 He who belongs to Ahab and dies in the city, the dogs will eat, and he who dies in the field, the birds of the sky will eat.'"
111Kg 21:25 Still, there was no one like Ahab, who devoted himself to do what was evil in the LORD's sight, because his wife Jezebel incited him.
111Kg 21:26 He committed the most detestable acts by going after idols as the Amorites had, whom the LORD had dispossessed before the Israelites.
111Kg 21:27 When Ahab heard these words, he tore his clothes, put sackcloth over his body, and fasted. He lay down in sackcloth and walked around subdued.
111Kg 21:28 Then the word of the LORD came to Elijah the Tishbite:
111Kg 21:29 "Have you seen how Ahab has humbled himself before Me? I will not bring the disaster during his lifetime, because he has humbled himself before Me. I will bring the disaster on his house during his son's lifetime."
111Kg 22:1 There was a lull of three years without war between Aram and Israel.
111Kg 22:2 However, in the third year, Jehoshaphat king of Judah went to visit the king of Israel.
111Kg 22:3 The king of Israel had said to his servants, "Don't you know that Ramoth-gilead is ours, but we have failed to take it from the hand of the king of Aram?"
111Kg 22:4 So he asked Jehoshaphat, "Will you go with me to fight Ramoth-gilead?" Jehoshaphat replied to the king of Israel, "I am as you are, my people as your people, my horses as your horses."
111Kg 22:5 But Jehoshaphat said to the king of Israel, "First, please ask what the LORD's will is."
111Kg 22:6 So the king of Israel gathered the prophets, about 400 men, and asked them, "Should I go against Ramoth-gilead for war or should I refrain?" They replied, "March up, and the Lord will hand it over to the king."
111Kg 22:7 But Jehoshaphat asked, "Isn't there a prophet of Yahweh here any more? Let's ask him."
111Kg 22:8 The king of Israel said to Jehoshaphat, "There is still one man who can ask the LORD, but I hate him because he never prophesies good about me, but only disaster. He is Micaiah son of Imlah." "The king shouldn't say that!" Jehoshaphat replied.
111Kg 22:9 So the king of Israel called an officer and said, "Hurry [and get] Micaiah son of Imlah!"
111Kg 22:10 Now the king of Israel and Jehoshaphat king of Judah, clothed in royal attire, were each sitting on his own throne. They were on the threshing floor at the entrance to Samaria's gate, and all the prophets were prophesying in front of them.
111Kg 22:11 Then Zedekiah son of Chenaanah made iron horns and said, "This is what the LORD says: 'You will gore the Arameans with these until they are finished off.'"
111Kg 22:12 And all the prophets were prophesying the same: "March up to Ramoth-gilead and succeed, for the LORD will hand it over to the king."
111Kg 22:13 The messenger who went to call Micaiah instructed him, "Look, the words of the prophets are unanimously favorable for the king. So let your words be like theirs, and speak favorably."
111Kg 22:14 But Micaiah said, "As the LORD lives, I will say whatever the LORD says to me."
111Kg 22:15 So he went to the king, and the king asked him, "Micaiah, should we go to Ramoth-gilead for war, or should we refrain?" Micaiah told him, "March up and succeed. The LORD will hand it over to the king."
111Kg 22:16 But the king said to him, "How many times must I make you swear not to tell me anything but the truth in the name of the LORD?"
111Kg 22:17 So Micaiah said: I saw all Israel scattered on the hills like sheep without a shepherd. And the LORD said, 'They have no master; let everyone return home in peace.'
111Kg 22:18 So the king of Israel said to Jehoshaphat, "Didn't I tell you he never prophesies good about me, but only disaster?"
111Kg 22:19 Then Micaiah said, "Therefore, hear the word of the LORD: I saw the LORD sitting on His throne, and the whole heavenly host was standing by Him at His right hand and at His left hand.
111Kg 22:20 And the LORD said, 'Who will entice Ahab to march up and fall at Ramoth-gilead?' So one was saying this and another was saying that.
111Kg 22:21 "Then a spirit came forward, stood before the LORD, and said, 'I will entice him.'
111Kg 22:22 "The LORD asked him, 'How?' "He said, 'I will go and become a lying spirit in the mouth of all his prophets.' "Then He said, 'You will certainly entice him and prevail. Go and do that.'
111Kg 22:23 "You see, the LORD has put a lying spirit into the mouth of all these prophets of yours, and the LORD has pronounced disaster against you."
111Kg 22:24 Then Zedekiah son of Chenaanah came up, hit Micaiah in the face, and demanded, "Did the Spirit of the LORD leave me to speak to you?"
111Kg 22:25 Micaiah replied, "You will soon see when you go to hide yourself in an inner chamber on that day."
111Kg 22:26 Then the king of Israel ordered, "Take Micaiah and return him to Amon, the governor of the city, and to Joash, the king's son,
111Kg 22:27 and say, 'This is what the king says: Put this guy in prison and feed him only bread and water until I come back safely.'"
111Kg 22:28 But Micaiah said, "If you ever return safely, the LORD has not spoken through me." Then he said, "Listen, all you people!"
111Kg 22:29 Then the king of Israel and Judah's King Jehoshaphat went up to Ramoth-gilead.
111Kg 22:30 But the king of Israel said to Jehoshaphat, "I will disguise myself and go into battle, but you wear your royal attire." So the king of Israel disguised himself and went into battle.
111Kg 22:31 Now the king of Aram had ordered his 32 chariot commanders, "Do not fight with anyone at all except the king of Israel."
111Kg 22:32 When the chariot commanders saw Jehoshaphat, they shouted, "He must be the king of Israel!" So they turned to fight against him, but Jehoshaphat cried out.
111Kg 22:33 When the chariot commanders saw that he was not the king of Israel, they turned back from pursuing him.
111Kg 22:34 But a man drew his bow without taking special aim and struck the king of Israel through the joints of his armor. So he said to his charioteer, "Turn around and take me out of the battle, for I am badly wounded!"
111Kg 22:35 The battle raged throughout that day, and the king was propped up in his chariot facing the Arameans. He died that evening, and blood from his wound flowed into the bottom of the chariot.
111Kg 22:36 Then the cry rang out in the army as the sun set, declaring: Each man to his own city, and each man to his own land!
111Kg 22:37 So the king died and was brought to Samaria. They buried the king in Samaria.
111Kg 22:38 Then someone washed the chariot at the pool of Samaria. The dogs licked up his blood, and the prostitutes bathed [in it], according to the word of the LORD that He had spoken.
111Kg 22:39 The rest of the events of Ahab's [reign], along with all his accomplishments, the ivory palace he built, and all the cities he built, are written about in the Historical Record of Israel's Kings.
111Kg 22:40 Ahab rested with his fathers, and his son Ahaziah became king in his place.
111Kg 22:41 Jehoshaphat son of Asa became king over Judah in the fourth year of Israel's King Ahab.
111Kg 22:42 Jehoshaphat was 35 years old when he became king; he reigned 25 years in Jerusalem. His mother's name was Azubah daughter of Shilhi.
111Kg 22:43 He walked in all the ways of his father Asa; he did not turn away from them but did what was right in the LORD's sight. However, the high places were not taken away; the people still sacrificed and burned incense on the high places.
111Kg 22:44 Jehoshaphat also made peace with the king of Israel.
111Kg 22:45 The rest of the events of Jehoshaphat's [reign], along with the might he exercised and how he waged war, are written about in the Historical Record of Judah's Kings.
111Kg 22:46 He removed from the land the rest of the male shrine prostitutes who were left from the days of his father Asa.
111Kg 22:47 There was no king in Edom; a deputy served as king.
111Kg 22:48 Jehoshaphat made ships of Tarshish to go to Ophir for gold, but they did not go because the ships were wrecked at Ezion-geber.
111Kg 22:49 At that time, Ahaziah son of Ahab said to Jehoshaphat, "Let my servants go with your servants in the ships," but Jehoshaphat was not willing.
111Kg 22:50 Jehoshaphat rested with his fathers and was buried with his fathers in the city of his forefather David. His son Jehoram became king in his place.
111Kg 22:51 Ahaziah son of Ahab became king over Israel in Samaria in the seventeenth year of Judah's King Jehoshaphat; he reigned over Israel two years.
111Kg 22:52 He did what was evil in the LORD's sight. He walked in the way of his father, in the way of his mother, and in the way of Jeroboam son of Nebat, who had caused Israel to sin.
111Kg 22:53 He served Baal and worshiped him. He provoked the LORD God of Israel just as his father had done.
